## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## docs-refresh v0.17.0
##
## v0.17.0 — CONVERGENCE HARDENING (asymptote enforcement). The
## 2026-06-23 dogfood (run on a scoped doc diff, diff_since=origin/main)
## looped ~16 review iterations to its `review_loop(15)` ceiling
## without converging, never reaching prepare_commit. Root causes
## (per CLAUDE.md "Review loops must converge to an asymptote"):
##
##  1. STREAK ASYMMETRY (LOW-CONFIDENCE). The `stop` formula
##     compared `input.approved` (raw) on the current side against
##     `loop.review_loop.previous_output.approved` (the previous
##     streak_check's LAUNDERED `approved`, which folded in
##     `confidence == 'low'`). So a CURRENT low-confidence rejection
##     with non-zero blockers reset the streak, while a PREVIOUS
##     low-confidence rejection didn't — pure noise oscillated the
##     gate. Fixed by also laundering the current side of `stop`:
##     `(input.approved || input.confidence == 'low' || input.blocker_count == 0)`.
##
##  2. NO RE-LITIGATION GUARD. Reviewers received the previous
##     verdict via `loop.review_loop.previous_output` but had no
##     instruction to refrain from re-raising items the previous
##     reviewer already adjudicated (dismissed or that the fixer
##     pushed back). With unverifiable `symbol_ref` candidates that
##     stay in the manifest every iter (CamelCase prose, archived
##     refs), each new reviewer wasted tool calls re-checking
##     items that were already settled. Fixed by:
##       a. Accumulating `cumulative_dismissed_pairs` (the union of
##          every reviewer's `audited_pairs` when they raised zero
##          blockers — i.e. confirmed-not-drift items) into
##          `streak_state`, then feeding it into both reviewers via
##          the alt→reviewer edges.
##       b. Accumulating `cumulative_pushback` (union of every
##          fixer pushback across families) into `streak_state`,
##          then feeding it into both reviewers alongside the
##          last-iter `prior_pushback`.
##       c. Adding an explicit "DO NOT re-raise without NEW
##          evidence" clause to `review_system` and to both
##          `review_user_*` prompts.
##
##  3. PREVIOUS VERDICT CONFIDENCE INVISIBLE. `streak_state` did
##     not carry `confidence`, so `loop.review_loop.previous_output`
##     showed reviewers a verdict shape without confidence. They
##     could not tell whether the previous family's rejection was
##     intuition-level (low) or evidence-backed (high), defeating
##     the monotonic-trend signal. Fixed by adding `confidence` to
##     `streak_state` and surfacing it in the prior-verdict prompt
##     stanza.
##
## v0.3.0 — DEFAULT-CREATE (operator-directed): when scan_docs finds
## ZERO documentation files in scope, the `author_docs` node creates
## the docs directory (`docs_dir` var, DEFAULT "docs") and authors an
## initial documentation set from the code; the run then loops back
## through scan_docs (author_rescan) and the normal review/refresh loop
## polishes + commits it. So docs-refresh refreshes from zero, not only
## edits pre-existing files. (The earlier doc-align → docs-refresh
## rename — operator-directed alongside this — is also complete.)
##
## Refreshes a repo's documentation against the actual current state of
## the code: detects mismatches between docs (README, docs/*.md,
## CLAUDE.md, bundled skills, optionally Go code comments) and the code,
## fixes the DOCUMENTATION (never the code), and auto-commits on
## convergence. When a repo has NO docs yet, it bootstraps an initial
## set first (see DEFAULT-CREATE above).
##
## v0.2.0 fixes 7 issues uncovered by the v0.1.0 dogfood run on
## this repo:
##  1. Template substitution bug: prior fix iteration's
##     `code_files_touched` was passed via {{outputs.fix_*.X}}
##     in the user prompt, which iterion does NOT auto-substitute
##     (only edge `with {}` triggers substitution). The G4 gate
##     therefore never fired in reviewers. Fixed by routing
##     prior_code_files_touched_{claude,gpt} through the edge.
##  2. Coverage threshold is now MECHANICAL: streak_check
##     computes the cumulative file-level coverage (distinct
##     doc_paths in cumulative_audited_docs over doc_count) and
##     bakes a coverage gate into the `stop` formula. Claude's
##     iter 2 in v0.1.0 approved with only 13/51 audited and the
##     streak was nearly armed — the mechanical gate prevents
##     that drift.
##  3. reviewer_gpt now uses `session: inherit` after the first
##     iteration so subsequent reviews ride on top of fix_gpt's
##     session (large prompt-cache benefit). v0.1.0 burned $7.49
##     on a single fresh-session GPT review of the workspace.
##  4. scan_docs auto-excludes the bot's own bundle via
##     `bundle_self_path` var — when docs-refresh is run on a repo
##     that contains its own source, the bot won't try to
##     "align" its own skills/main.bot to itself.
##  5. Incremental mode: when `diff_since` is set, scan_docs
##     emits `recently_changed_code_files[]` (from
##     `git diff <ref>...HEAD --name-only`) as a HINT to reviewers
##     so they can prioritise docs that reference recent code
##     churn. The full doc footprint is still audited — the
##     hint is non-authoritative.
##  6. `anchor_kind` enum (symbol | line_range | removed |
##     external) added to mismatch shape per
##     doc-mismatch-taxonomy.md. Discipline gain: reviewers must
##     classify the citation precision, which makes the G3
##     round-trip auditable.
##  7. Final-report hint: the v0.1.0 commit message embedded the
##     report inline. v0.2.0 points users at `iterion report
##     --run-id <id>` (already exists) instead — see README.md.
##
## Workflow shape mirrors branch_improve_loop: alternating
## claude_code (opus) and claw (gpt-5.5) reviewers, deterministic
## streak_check requiring two consecutive cross-family approvals
## AND coverage ≥ coverage_target_pct, prepare_commit +
## commit_changes finalize on convergence.
##
## Inviolable rules (enforced by skills + prompts):
##   1. Docs follow code; code does NOT follow docs.
##   2. Fixer writeable set: `.md` files in scope + Go code
##      comments when `go_comment_globs` is non-empty.
##   3. The audit footprint is determined by the scanner tool,
##      not by agents.
##   4. Escape valve: when the doc is correct and the code is
##      wrong, set `is_code_bug=true` and call `ask_user`.
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

vars:
  workspace_dir: string = "${PROJECT_DIR}"

  ## Doc footprint scope (comma-separated globs). The scan_docs
  ## tool node enumerates files matching these globs once, at run
  ## start. Hidden / vendored / runtime dirs (.iterion, .works,
  ## .claude, vendor, node_modules, .git, dist, build, out) are
  ## excluded unconditionally inside the scanner; the bot's own
  ## bundle is excluded when `bundle_self_path` is set.
  ## UNIVERSAL DEFAULT: docs-refresh documents ANY repo, so the default
  ## footprint is the conventions common to most projects (root +
  ## nested READMEs, a docs/ tree, CLAUDE.md). Repo-specific doc
  ## locations (e.g. iterion's `examples/*/skills/*.md` bundle docs)
  ## are added per-repo via --var, never baked into the catalog
  ## default. See "Catalog bots are repo-agnostic" in CLAUDE.md.
  doc_globs: string = "README.md,docs/**/*.md,**/README.md,CLAUDE.md,**/CLAUDE.md"

  ## Go code comment scope (comma-separated globs). Empty (default)
  ## means: do NOT audit Go function/package comments — speeds up
  ## first runs.
  go_comment_globs: string = ""

  ## Code scope reviewers may grep / read to verify doc claims.
  ## UNIVERSAL DEFAULT: empty = reviewers may grep the whole
  ## workspace (minus `excluded_dirs`). A language/layout-specific
  ## scope (e.g. iterion's `pkg/**/*.go,cmd/**/*.go`) is a per-repo
  ## --var override, never the catalog default — docs-refresh must run
  ## on Python / Rust / TS / Go repos identically out of the box.
  code_scope_globs: string = ""

  ## Optional free-text notes pinning the reviewers' attention.
  scope_notes: string = ""

  ## Loop bounds.
  max_review_iterations: int = 15
  max_recovery_iterations: int = 20

  ## Coverage threshold (percentage of `doc_files` that must
  ## appear in `cumulative_audited_docs` before stop=true can
  ## fire). Default 80 — high enough to defeat the "rubber-stamp
  ## after a partial audit" failure mode seen in v0.1.0, low
  ## enough to allow approval when a small tail of files is
  ## genuinely irrelevant for this iteration's diff.
  coverage_target_pct: int = 80

  ## Auto-exclusion (fix 4). When non-empty, scan_docs excludes
  ## any file whose path starts with this prefix from the doc
  ## footprint. Set to `bots/docs-refresh` when running docs-refresh
  ## on the iterion repo itself; otherwise leave empty.
  bundle_self_path: string = ""

  ## Incremental mode (fix 5). When non-empty, scan_docs computes
  ## `git diff <diff_since>...HEAD --name-only` and surfaces the
  ## result as `recently_changed_code_files`. Reviewers receive
  ## this as a HINT to prioritise docs that reference those files
  ## — the full doc footprint is still mandatory coverage. Useful
  ## for nightly / per-PR runs (`--var diff_since=main`).
  diff_since: string = ""

  ## Hard-excluded directories (v0.8.0). Comma-separated list of
  ## directory names whose presence anywhere in a path
  ## disqualifies it from `doc_files` (regardless of `doc_globs`).
  ## Defaults exclude runtime / scratch / vendor / artifact dirs
  ## that should never be audited. Override to enable multi-repo
  ## audit — e.g. drop `.works` to include sibling repos checked
  ## out under `.works/<repo>/`. Setting to empty disables all
  ## exclusion (NOT recommended — picks up `.git/`).
  excluded_dirs: string = ".iterion,.works,.claude,vendor,node_modules,.git,dist,build,out"

  ## Code-surface scan scope (v0.6.0). Globs for the
  ## `scan_code_surface` tool — a counter-omission audit that greps
  ## the code for "publicly-exposed identifiers" docs ought to
  ## mention (CLI commands, flags, diagnostic codes) and checks each
  ## appears in at least one doc.
  ##
  ## OPT-IN / NON-UNIVERSAL: the scanner's extraction patterns are
  ## currently specialised for a Cobra-CLI + custom-diagnostic-code
  ## repo (it greps cobra `Use:` literals and `Cxxx`-style codes —
  ## see scan_code_surface below). That heuristic only produces
  ## meaningful output on repos shaped like that (e.g. iterion). So
  ## the catalog DEFAULT is empty = surface scan DISABLED, and
  ## docs-refresh does a universal doc↔code drift audit. A CLI/DSL repo
  ## opts in per-run, e.g.
  ##   --var cli_surface_globs="cmd/myapp/*.go" \
  ##   --var diagnostic_surface_globs="internal/diag/*.go"
  ## Generalising the scanner's patterns to other stacks is tracked
  ## as a follow-up; until then, leave empty for non-Cobra repos.
  cli_surface_globs: string = ""
  diagnostic_surface_globs: string = ""

  ## v0.15.0: cap on the reviewer's per-iteration working set —
  ## build_manifest sorts candidates by severity (drifted CLI
  ## surface > diagnostic > file_ref > symbol_ref > unverifiable)
  ## then takes the top N. Tuning history:
  ##   - 150 (initial): reviewer hit error_max_turns at iter 0 —
  ##     thorough spot-checks across 13 turns blew the budget.
  ##   - 40 (v0.15.1): smaller per-iter slice, reviewer fits in
  ##     tool_max_steps:15 with room for structured output. The
  ##     bot ITERATES — iter 1 fixes ~30, iter 2 sees ~30 more
  ##     (or coverage rises if the iter 1 fix dropped drifts
  ##     across families). Convergence over fewer-larger iters.
  max_drift_candidates: int = 40

  ## v0.16.0 (doc-count chunking): cap on the number of DISTINCT
  ## docs whose candidates may land in any single reviewer iteration.
  ## Applied AFTER the severity-priority sort and BEFORE the
  ## max_drift_candidates cap, so the slice keeps the most severe
  ## candidates AND fits inside the per-iter doc budget.
  ##
  ## Why this exists: with the v0.15.0 manifest pattern the candidate
  ## count was already bounded (40), but the reviewer still spot-
  ## checks high-severity drifts via read_file / grep. On large doc
  ## footprints (89 docs / 175+ drifts on this repo) the spot-check
  ## tool calls accumulate in the conversation and blow the gpt-5.5
  ## ChatGPT-forfait context window after 4-5 turns
  ## (context_length_exceeded; finding
  ## `2026-05-24-docs-refresh-reviewer-gpt-context-exhaustion.md`).
  ## Bounding the chunk by DOC count caps the file surface area the
  ## reviewer is tempted to spot-check, even when the candidate
  ## count is well under max_drift_candidates.
  ##
  ## Convergence is unchanged: streak_check still gates on the
  ## anchor-level coverage_pct (verified / total across ALL docs).
  ## The chunk only narrows what the reviewer SEES per iter; as the
  ## fixer resolves drifts in chunk N, chunk N+1 surfaces the next
  ## tier of severity (which naturally covers different docs).
  ##
  ## Default 30 matches the issue acceptance criterion. Setting to
  ## 0 disables doc-chunking (legacy candidate-count bound only).
  max_review_chunk_docs: int = 30

  ## v0.15.4: identifier of the tracker issue this run was dispatched
  ## from. Used by mark_issue_for_review at the end of the workflow
  ## to transition the issue out of `ready` so the dispatcher doesn't
  ## re-pick it on the next poll. Filled by the dispatcher via
  ## `vars.issue_id: "{{issue.identifier}}"` in dispatch_defaults.
  ## Empty string when run outside the dispatcher (manual CLI run);
  ## mark_issue_for_review is then a no-op.
  issue_id: string = ""

  ## Inter-run audit cache (v0.5.0). Path to the JSON cache file
  ## that stores `{doc_path: {sha, refs: [{path, sha}]}}` from the
  ## previous successful run. scan_docs reads this and emits
  ## `pre_verified_docs` for entries whose doc content AND all
  ## cited code-file SHAs are unchanged. update_audit_cache (the
  ## terminal tool node) writes the merged state after commit.
  ## Empty string disables both reads and writes — useful for
  ## the first run on a workspace or when you want a guaranteed
  ## fresh audit.
  ##
  ## UNIVERSAL DEFAULT: a repo-root dotfile, NOT iterion's `.iterion/`
  ## store dir — docs-refresh running on someone else's repo must not
  ## scatter `.iterion/` paths into their tree. Add the cache file to
  ## the target repo's .gitignore (or leave empty to disable).
  audit_cache_path: string = ".docs-refresh-cache.json"

  ## DEFAULT-CREATE (v0.3.0): when scan_docs finds ZERO documentation
  ## files in scope (a repo with no docs yet), the `author_docs` node
  ## creates this directory and authors an initial documentation set
  ## there from the code; the run then re-scans and the normal review/
  ## refresh loop polishes + commits it. Repo-relative; DEFAULT "docs"
  ## (the universal convention, already covered by the default doc_globs
  ## entry "docs/**/*.md"). Override per-run with `--var docs_dir=<dir>`;
  ## if you point it OUTSIDE the default doc_globs, widen doc_globs too
  ## so the post-authoring re-scan picks the new docs up.
  docs_dir: string = "docs"


## ─── Prompts ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

prompt review_system:
  You are a rigorous documentation reviewer for the `docs-refresh`
  workflow. Your job is to detect mismatches between project
  documentation and the actual current state of the code, and to
  produce a structured verdict.

  LOAD YOUR SKILLS FIRST. The workflow ships five skills under
  `.claude/skills/` describing the discipline you MUST follow:
    - `docs-refresh.md` — operating playbook, the why and the
      inviolable rules
    - `doc-mismatch-taxonomy.md` — the 11 mismatch_kind enum
      values AND the `anchor_kind` enum you must use to tag
      every blocker
    - `doc-scope-enumeration.md` — the immutable scan_docs
      footprint contract
    - `doc-verification-checklist.md` — the STEP-0 preamble you
      MUST run before voting approved=true (now includes the
      mechanical coverage gate semantics)
    - `anti-facade-fix-rules.md` — what a façade fix looks like

  Read them before reasoning. Then run STEP 0 through STEP 6 of
  `doc-verification-checklist.md` literally.

  THE INVIOLABLE RULES (restated for emphasis):
   1. Docs follow code; code does NOT follow docs. You correct
      documentation to match the code, not the other way around.
   2. The audit footprint is `input.doc_files[]` from `scan_docs`.
      It is immutable. You cannot drop files; if you cannot verify
      a file, raise a coverage gap, do not silently skip.
   3. If a doc is correct and the code is wrong, set
      `is_code_bug=true` on the blocker and call `ask_user`.
   4. **G4 GATE (now wired correctly in v0.2.0)** — examine
      `input.prior_code_files_touched_claude` and
      `input.prior_code_files_touched_gpt`. Both MUST be `[]`.
      If either is non-empty, raise an automatic blocker
      (`severity: high`, `confidence: high`,
      `mismatch_kind: stale_behavior_description`) describing
      the contract violation. v0.1.0 routed these via the
      outputs-of-fixer template form which iterion does NOT
      substitute in prompts — the gate never fired. v0.2.0
      passes them via the edge `with {}` block.
   5. **COVERAGE GATE (new in v0.2.0)** — `input.coverage_pct`
      shows the current cumulative coverage (% of `doc_files`
      present as `doc_path` in `cumulative_audited_docs`). The
      compute node `streak_check` mechanically blocks
      convergence (`stop=false`) when `coverage_pct <
      input.coverage_target_pct`. You may still vote
      `approved=true` on a partial audit when you're confident in
      what you have, but the workflow won't terminate until
      coverage meets the threshold across both families.
   6. **SCOPE-HONESTY GATE (v0.13.0 — threshold gated in the
      tool, not the prompt)** — `input.cumulative_chronic_paths`
      is a (possibly empty) DEDUPLICATED list of doc paths the
      deterministic `enforce_fix_scope` tool has had to revert
      ≥ 3 times across the run so far. The threshold is computed
      inside the tool; you receive ONLY the thresholded result.

      Rules:
       a. If `cumulative_chronic_paths` is non-empty, raise ONE
          blocker per element with:
            mismatch_kind:   `stale_behavior_description`
            severity:        high
            confidence:      high
            doc_path:        the chronic path
            code_anchor:     "fixer scope contract"
            anchor_kind:     "filesystem_path"
            code_state:      "fixer has modified this path on
                             ≥3 iters without declaring it in
                             modified_doc_files; enforce_fix_scope
                             reverted each time. The fix
                             declaration is the writeable-set
                             contract."
            suggested_fix:   "Next fix iteration MUST either
                             include this path in
                             modified_doc_files (if it legitimately
                             needs the edit) OR leave it untouched.
                             Silent edits are mechanically
                             reverted."
       b. If `cumulative_chronic_paths` is EMPTY, say absolutely
          NOTHING about scope, reverts, modified_doc_files, or
          fixer discipline. Do NOT embed scope hints in other
          blockers' `suggested_fix` or `code_state`. Do NOT
          mention enforce_fix_scope. The information you would
          need to talk about scope is not present in your
          inputs — TREAT IT AS IF IT DOESN'T EXIST.

          (Why this rule is strict: v0.12 exposed raw revert
          counts to the reviewer. The reviewer used them
          adaptively, hinting at threshold=1-2 inline inside
          unrelated blockers. The fixer ignored the hints. The
          net effect was Goodhart-prone reviewer side-talk
          with zero behavioural change. v0.13 fixes this by
          construction — the raw counts are no longer in
          your inputs.)
       c. A scope-honesty blocker is in ADDITION to your normal
          audit findings, never in place of them.

  HOW TO USE `input.recently_changed_code_files` (fix 5):
   This list contains the code files modified since
   `vars.diff_since` (empty when diff_since is unset). When
   non-empty, prioritise docs that reference any of those files
   — those are the most likely sites of drift. The full
   `input.doc_files[]` footprint is still your audit ceiling;
   recently-changed is a HINT, not a scope reduction.

  CONVERGENCE — DO NOT RE-LITIGATE (v0.17.0):
   This is a review LOOP that must converge to an asymptote
   (settle into a stable approved state and stop). Re-raising an
   item the loop has already adjudicated is the classic
   oscillation driver — it resets the streak gate and wastes the
   iteration budget.

   Three signals tell you what has already been settled:

   a. `input.cumulative_dismissed_pairs` — the union of every
      `doc::value` pair that a prior reviewer (any family) put
      into `audited_pairs` WHILE raising zero blockers on that
      iteration. I.e. items the cross-family review already
      decided are NOT drift. Do NOT re-raise any pair in this
      list as a blocker UNLESS you have NEW EVIDENCE the prior
      adjudication missed (e.g. you ran `grep` on the live tree
      and found a genuine drift the previous reviewer overlooked).
      If you must re-raise, state the new evidence in the
      blocker's `code_state` / `suggested_fix` explicitly so the
      cross-family reviewer can spot-check.

   b. `input.cumulative_pushback` — the union of every blocker
      the FIXER pushed back (across both families) with its
      justification. The fixer has already declined these items
      as false-positives or `is_code_bug`. Do NOT re-raise the
      same blocker unless you can rebut the fixer's
      justification with NEW evidence.

   c. `loop.review_loop.previous_output.blockers` +
      `previous_output.confidence` — the previous reviewer's
      verdict (other family, last iter — visible to you below
      the gates section). Verdicts must trend monotonically: if
      the previous reviewer raised N blockers with high
      confidence and the fixer applied a fix, you should expect
      ≤N residual blockers (commonly 0). If you raise MORE
      blockers, justify what changed (the fix introduced
      regression, the fixer pushed back a real drift, etc.).

   Default posture: when an item appears in (a) or (b), DISMISS
   it (do not add to blockers, do not re-add to `audited_pairs`
   unless you re-investigated) and spend the tool-call budget on
   genuinely NEW drift surfaces. The manifest is deterministic —
   it re-extracts the same unverifiable `symbol_ref` candidates
   every iter; the do-not-relitigate rule is what stops the
   reviewer from re-judging them every iter.

  HOW TO USE THE CHUNK FIELDS (v0.16.0):
   `input.chunked`, `input.chunk_doc_count`, and
   `input.docs_with_drift_count` describe this iter's slice of
   the global drift set. When `chunked=true`, you are seeing
   candidates from at most `max_review_chunk_docs` distinct docs;
   the remainder are deferred to subsequent iters as the fixer
   clears earlier severity tiers. This is deterministic, not a
   coverage gap — your job is unchanged: adjudicate the
   candidates you DO see. The streak gate uses
   `manifest_coverage_pct` (anchor-level, across ALL docs), so a
   chunked iter cannot terminate the workflow prematurely.

  PATH-OF-LEAST-RESISTANCE WARNING:
   You will be tempted to focus on docs colocated with code that
   has been recently changed. Resist. Audit every file in
   `input.doc_files[]` over the course of the loop.

  HUMAN ESCALATION:
   When you hit genuine ambiguity, call `ask_user` with a precise
   question. Use this sparingly — for ordinary judgment calls,
   decide yourself and lower `confidence` if uncertain.

prompt review_user_claude:
  Adjudicate the drift candidates in {{vars.workspace_dir}}'s
  documentation. The deterministic `build_manifest` tool has
  already enumerated every doc anchor (file refs, CLI commands,
  CLI flags, diagnostic codes, exported symbols) and verified
  each against the live code state. Your job is the SEMANTIC
  pass over the candidates it could not auto-resolve.

  Iteration: {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}
  Family: claude
  Workspace: {{vars.workspace_dir}}
  Scope notes (operator's attention pin):
  {{vars.scope_notes}}

  ## Manifest summary (deterministic, v0.15.0)
  Total docs scanned:       {{input.total_docs}}
  Total anchors enumerated: {{input.total_anchors}}
  Verified:                 {{input.verified_anchors}}
  Drifted:                  {{input.drifted_anchors}}
  Unverifiable:             {{input.unverifiable_anchors}}
  Mechanical coverage:      {{input.manifest_coverage_pct}}%
  Coverage threshold:       {{input.coverage_target_pct}}%

  ## This iteration's chunk (v0.16.0 doc-count chunking)
  Docs with remaining drift: {{input.docs_with_drift_count}}
  Docs in this chunk:        {{input.chunk_doc_count}} (cap: {{input.max_review_chunk_docs}})
  Chunked this iter:         {{input.chunked}}
  When `Chunked this iter: true`, drifts in the deferred docs will
  surface in a later iter as the fixer clears this chunk. Do NOT
  vote `approved=true` based on the chunk alone — the streak gate
  uses anchor-level mechanical coverage across ALL docs.

  ## Drift candidates (the working set — bounded to top
  ## {{vars.max_drift_candidates}} by severity, then to candidates
  ## from at most {{vars.max_review_chunk_docs}} distinct docs)
  Each candidate carries `{doc, line, kind, value, status,
  evidence, excerpt}`. `status` is one of:
   - drifted     — anchor extracted from the doc, NOT found in
                   the live code (file missing, CLI flag absent
                   from scan_code_surface, diagnostic code not
                   in the parser, …). Highest signal.
   - unverifiable — symbol_ref the heuristic couldn't resolve.
                   Often prose words that look like CamelCase,
                   archived examples, or external refs. Treat
                   with care; downgrade to false-positive when
                   the doc context makes it clear.

  Candidates:
  {{input.drift_candidates}}

  ## Cross-family context

  Previous reviewer's verdict (other family, last iteration —
  empty on iter 0). Note the prior `confidence` — verdicts MUST
  trend monotonically (see review_system "DO NOT RE-LITIGATE"):
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Items the fixer pushed back as is_code_bug / false-positive
  ON THE LAST ITERATION:
  {{input.prior_pushback}}
  Justification:
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  ## Already-adjudicated (do NOT re-raise without NEW evidence)

  Pairs that prior reviewers (any family) marked as not-drift
  across the ENTIRE run (cumulative). Each entry is a
  `doc::value` string. Per review_system, dismiss these on
  sight unless you have new evidence:
  {{input.cumulative_dismissed_pairs}}

  Every blocker the fixer has pushed back across the run
  (cumulative). Per review_system, do NOT re-raise unless you
  can rebut the fixer's justification with new evidence:
  {{input.cumulative_pushback}}

  ## Gates

  G4 — fixers must NEVER touch code. Both fields below MUST be
  empty arrays; non-empty = automatic contract-violation blocker
  with severity:high:
   - claude fixer: {{input.prior_code_files_touched_claude}}
   - gpt fixer:    {{input.prior_code_files_touched_gpt}}

  SCOPE-HONESTY (v0.13.0) — `cumulative_chronic_paths` lists
  paths the fixer has tried to silently edit ≥3 times. If
  non-empty, raise one scope-honesty blocker per element per
  review_system rule 6a. If empty: stay silent on the topic
  per rule 6b.
   - chronic paths: {{input.cumulative_chronic_paths}}

  ## Your verdict — emit ONLY structured output

  For each candidate in `input.drift_candidates`, decide:
    A. confirm  — real drift, raise as a blocker pointed at the
                  doc::value pair, suggested_fix explains the
                  doc edit (NOT a code edit)
    B. dismiss  — false positive (prose, archived example,
                  external reference, etc.). Do NOT raise a
                  blocker; the manifest will keep listing it
                  but the bot won't act.
    C. code_bug — doc is correct, code is wrong / removed in
                  error. Raise a blocker with `is_code_bug:true`;
                  the fixer will escalate via ask_user.

  Spot-check budget: you have `tool_max_steps: 25`. **Trust the
  manifest by default.** The deterministic verifier already ran
  every anchor against the live code; its `status` field is
  authoritative for ~95% of candidates. Spend tool calls ONLY on
  the top 2-3 highest-severity drifts when you suspect the
  verifier missed semantic context (e.g. a "drifted" cli_command
  that's actually a stdlib name). Aim for ≤10 tool calls per
  iter so you have headroom to emit structured output. Bulk-
  `confirm` the rest based on the manifest's evidence alone —
  that's the whole point of the manifest pattern.

  CRITICAL — re-litigation costs the streak. If a candidate
  appears in `input.cumulative_dismissed_pairs` or
  `input.cumulative_pushback`, the default is DISMISS without
  spending a tool call. Spending tool calls on already-settled
  items is the exact oscillation pattern that blew past the
  iteration ceiling in the 2026-06-23 dogfood.

  Output schema (verdict_output):
   - approved: bool — true ONLY when blockers == [] AND
     manifest_coverage_pct >= coverage_target_pct
   - family: "claude"
   - blockers: structured mismatch objects (see
     `doc-mismatch-taxonomy.md`)
   - blocker_count: int == len(blockers)
   - fix_plan: concrete instruction set for the fixer (short)
   - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
   - audited_pairs: list of "doc_path::value" strings — one per
     candidate you reviewed (whether you confirmed, dismissed,
     or flagged code_bug). Lets the cross-family reviewer
     spot-check your work.
   - audited_docs: distinct doc_path values you touched
     (subset of input.all_audited_docs; manifest already
     covers all docs mechanically — this list is for the
     spot-check audit trail)
   - escalate_to_human: true if ANY blocker has is_code_bug=true

prompt review_user_gpt:
  Adjudicate the drift candidates in {{vars.workspace_dir}}'s
  documentation. The deterministic `build_manifest` tool has
  already enumerated every doc anchor and verified each against
  the live code state. Your job is the SEMANTIC pass over the
  candidates it could not auto-resolve.

  Iteration: {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}
  Family: gpt
  Workspace: {{vars.workspace_dir}}
  Scope notes (operator's attention pin):
  {{vars.scope_notes}}

  ## Manifest summary (deterministic, v0.15.0)
  Total docs scanned:       {{input.total_docs}}
  Total anchors enumerated: {{input.total_anchors}}
  Verified:                 {{input.verified_anchors}}
  Drifted:                  {{input.drifted_anchors}}
  Unverifiable:             {{input.unverifiable_anchors}}
  Mechanical coverage:      {{input.manifest_coverage_pct}}%
  Coverage threshold:       {{input.coverage_target_pct}}%

  ## This iteration's chunk (v0.16.0 doc-count chunking)
  Docs with remaining drift: {{input.docs_with_drift_count}}
  Docs in this chunk:        {{input.chunk_doc_count}} (cap: {{input.max_review_chunk_docs}})
  Chunked this iter:         {{input.chunked}}
  When `Chunked this iter: true`, drifts in the deferred docs will
  surface in a later iter as the fixer clears this chunk. Do NOT
  vote `approved=true` based on the chunk alone — the streak gate
  uses anchor-level mechanical coverage across ALL docs.

  ## Drift candidates (bounded by severity to top
  ## {{vars.max_drift_candidates}}, then to candidates from at most
  ## {{vars.max_review_chunk_docs}} distinct docs)
  Each candidate carries `{doc, line, kind, value, status,
  evidence, excerpt}`. `status` is one of:
   - drifted     — anchor extracted from the doc, NOT found in
                   the live code (file missing, CLI flag absent
                   from scan_code_surface, diagnostic code not
                   in the parser, …). Highest signal.
   - unverifiable — symbol_ref the heuristic couldn't resolve.
                   Often prose words that look like CamelCase,
                   archived examples, or external refs.

  Candidates:
  {{input.drift_candidates}}

  ## Cross-family context

  Previous reviewer's verdict (other family, last iteration —
  empty on iter 0). Note the prior `confidence` — verdicts MUST
  trend monotonically (see review_system "DO NOT RE-LITIGATE"):
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Items the fixer pushed back as is_code_bug / false-positive
  ON THE LAST ITERATION:
  {{input.prior_pushback}}
  Justification:
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  ## Already-adjudicated (do NOT re-raise without NEW evidence)

  Pairs that prior reviewers (any family) marked as not-drift
  across the ENTIRE run (cumulative). Each entry is a
  `doc::value` string. Per review_system, dismiss these on
  sight unless you have new evidence:
  {{input.cumulative_dismissed_pairs}}

  Every blocker the fixer has pushed back across the run
  (cumulative). Per review_system, do NOT re-raise unless you
  can rebut the fixer's justification with new evidence:
  {{input.cumulative_pushback}}

  ## Gates

  G4 — fixers must NEVER touch code. Both fields below MUST be
  empty arrays; non-empty = automatic contract-violation blocker
  with severity:high:
   - claude fixer: {{input.prior_code_files_touched_claude}}
   - gpt fixer:    {{input.prior_code_files_touched_gpt}}

  SCOPE-HONESTY (v0.13.0) — `cumulative_chronic_paths` lists
  paths the fixer has tried to silently edit ≥3 times. If
  non-empty, raise one scope-honesty blocker per element per
  review_system rule 6a. If empty: stay silent on the topic
  per rule 6b.
   - chronic paths: {{input.cumulative_chronic_paths}}

  ## Your verdict — emit ONLY structured output

  For each candidate in `input.drift_candidates`, decide:
    A. confirm  — real drift; raise a blocker pointed at the
                  doc::value pair with suggested_fix on the doc
    B. dismiss  — false positive (prose, archived, external)
    C. code_bug — doc correct, code wrong/removed in error;
                  raise blocker with `is_code_bug:true`

  Spot-check budget: `tool_max_steps: 25`. **Trust the manifest
  by default.** The deterministic verifier already ran every
  anchor against the live code. Spend tool calls ONLY on the
  top 2-3 highest-severity drifts you suspect the verifier
  missed semantically. Aim for ≤10 tool calls; bulk-confirm
  the rest.

  CRITICAL — re-litigation costs the streak. If a candidate
  appears in `input.cumulative_dismissed_pairs` or
  `input.cumulative_pushback`, the default is DISMISS without
  spending a tool call. Spending tool calls on already-settled
  items is the exact oscillation pattern that blew past the
  iteration ceiling in the 2026-06-23 dogfood.

  Output schema (verdict_output):
   - approved: bool — true ONLY when blockers == [] AND
     manifest_coverage_pct >= coverage_target_pct
   - family: "gpt"
   - blockers: structured mismatch objects (see
     `doc-mismatch-taxonomy.md`)
   - blocker_count: int == len(blockers)
   - fix_plan: concrete instruction set for the fixer (short)
   - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
   - audited_pairs: list of "doc_path::value" strings — one per
     candidate you reviewed (whether confirmed, dismissed, or
     flagged code_bug)
   - audited_docs: distinct doc_path values you touched
     (subset of input.all_audited_docs)
   - escalate_to_human: true if ANY blocker has is_code_bug=true

prompt fix_system:
  You are the fixer for the `docs-refresh` workflow. You apply
  corrections to DOCUMENTATION files based on blockers a reviewer
  has identified.

  LOAD YOUR SKILLS FIRST. Especially:
    - `anti-facade-fix-rules.md` — the discipline rules. A fix
      where your `summary` does not cite the tool invocation
      (read_file / grep) that verified the cited `code_anchor`
      is a façade.
    - `doc-mismatch-taxonomy.md` — the kind / severity meanings
      plus the `anchor_kind` enum (symbol | line_range | removed
      | external).
    - `doc-scope-enumeration.md` — what you may and may not
      write to.

  HARD CONSTRAINTS:
   1. Writeable extensions: `.md` only, AND (when go_comment_globs
      is non-empty) Go code comments inside files matching that
      scope. You may NEVER write to a `.go` statement, expression,
      or declaration body.
   2. `fix_output.code_files_touched[]` MUST be empty in your
      output. The next reviewer will flag non-empty as a workflow
      contract violation (now enforced via input.prior_code_files_touched_*
      thanks to the v0.2.0 edge routing fix).
   3. `fix_output.modified_doc_files[]` MUST be a subset of
      `input.doc_files` (the scanner footprint). You cannot
      introduce new doc files; you cannot edit docs outside scope.
   4. For each fix you apply, your `summary` MUST contain the
      tool invocation (`read_file` or `grep`) you used to verify
      the current code state at the cited `code_anchor`. Without
      that evidence the fix is a façade.

  ESCAPE VALVE:
   If a blocker has `is_code_bug=true`, do NOT attempt to fix it.
   Add it to `pushback` with a justification explaining that the
   doc appears correct and the code is the problem. Call
   `ask_user` to surface the question to the operator if you
   need confirmation.

  PUSHBACK:
   You may refuse a blocker by adding its exact description to
   `pushback[]` with a clear justification in
   `pushback_justification`.

prompt fix_user:
  Apply doc-only fixes for these blockers in
  {{vars.workspace_dir}}.

  Doc footprint (your writeable set, plus Go code comments inside
  go_comment_globs when non-empty):
  {{vars.doc_globs}}

  Go comment scope (empty = no Go comments may be edited):
  {{vars.go_comment_globs}}

  Blockers to address:
  {{input.blockers}}

  Fix plan from the reviewer:
  {{input.fix_plan}}

  For EACH blocker:
   1. Read the code at the cited `code_anchor` to verify the
      current state. Paste the tool invocation and an excerpt
      into your `summary`.
   2. If the blocker is genuine and is_code_bug is false: apply
      the fix to the doc. Run the negative-space check
      (`git grep` for stale cross-references to whatever you
      removed) and fix those too in the same pass.
   3. If `is_code_bug=true`: do NOT fix. Push back with a
      justification.
   4. If the blocker is a false positive: push back with
      justification.

  Output fields:
   - applied: true if at least one fix landed
   - summary: list of fixes with their tool-invocation evidence
   - modified_doc_files: exact list of repo-relative paths you
     wrote to (must be subset of scan_docs.doc_files)
   - code_files_touched: MUST be []
   - pushback: items refused
   - pushback_justification: explanation


## ─── Prompts : Default-create (author docs from zero) ──────────────

prompt author_docs_system:
  You are the doc author for the `docs-refresh` workflow, invoked on a
  repository that currently has NO documentation in scope. Your job is
  to BOOTSTRAP an initial documentation set by reading the code and
  writing accurate Markdown, so the run's normal review/refresh loop has
  something real to polish.

  Load the `docs-refresh.md` skill for the operating context.

  WHAT TO CREATE:
   - Create the docs directory (`{{input.docs_dir}}`) if it does not
     exist, and author your documentation there as `.md` files.
   - Author or refresh a top-level `README.md` if the repo has none — a
     short overview that links into `{{input.docs_dir}}/`.
   - Cover, at minimum: a project overview (what it is / what it does),
     how to build & run it, the high-level architecture or module map,
     and how to use the main entry points. Add further pages only where
     the code clearly warrants them — do not pad.

  HARD CONSTRAINTS:
   1. Documentation only — write `.md` files. NEVER modify source code,
      build files, or configuration.
   2. EVIDENCE OVER INVENTION. Every statement must reflect what the
      code actually does. Read the relevant files before describing
      them; never document aspirational or assumed behaviour. If you
      cannot verify a claim, omit it rather than guess.
   3. STACK-AGNOSTIC. This repo may be in ANY language. Detect the
      language / build system from the repo itself (manifest files,
      entry points, lockfiles) — never assume a particular ecosystem.
   4. Do NOT commit. A later step commits on convergence.

prompt author_docs_user:
  Author initial documentation for the repository at
  {{input.workspace_dir}}.

  Target docs directory (create if absent): {{input.docs_dir}}

  Recently changed code files (a hint, may be empty — non-authoritative):
  {{input.recently_changed_code_files}}

  Steps:
   1. Survey the repository to understand its purpose, language/stack,
      structure, and entry points (read manifest files, top-level
      directories, and the main entry file(s)).
   2. Create `{{input.docs_dir}}/` if needed and author the initial
      `.md` pages described in your system prompt, each grounded in what
      you read. Author/refresh a root `README.md` overview if missing.
   3. Keep each page focused and accurate; cross-link the pages.

  Output fields:
   - docs_created: true if you created at least one doc file
   - created_doc_files: repo-relative paths you wrote
   - summary: what you authored, and the evidence (files you read)
     behind the key claims


## ─── Prompts : Commit ──────────────────────────────────────────

prompt prepare_commit_system:
  Your job is to pick the EXACT set of doc files that should be
  committed to capture the alignment fixes applied during this
  run, and produce a semantic commit message. You do NOT run
  `git commit` yourself — a deterministic shell tool downstream
  stages your file list and applies your message.

  Procedure (in order):
   1. Run `git status` and `git diff HEAD` (read-only) to
      enumerate working-tree changes. `git status` ALSO lists NEW,
      untracked doc files (shown as `??`) — e.g. the initial set
      authored on a from-zero refresh of a repo that had no docs.
      INCLUDE those new `.md` files in the commit set. A brand-new
      file shows nothing under `git diff HEAD -- <file>` (it is not in
      HEAD yet), so confirm a new file by READING it, not by diffing —
      do not drop a new doc just because its diff is empty.
   2. Cross-reference with the scanner footprint (visible in your
      conversation history). The commit set must be a subset of
      that footprint, plus any Go file whose comments were edited
      (no Go file should be on the list with code changes —
      verify by running `git diff HEAD -- <file>` and confirming
      only comment lines changed).
   3. EXCLUDE any non-doc file. EXCLUDE any LLM scratch
      (`notes.md`, `plan.txt`, etc.). EXCLUDE editor scratch and
      build artefacts.
   4. Build the structured output:
       - type: "docs" (default) or "fix" (only when you fixed a
         demonstrably misleading code COMMENT that would have led
         readers astray)
       - scope: typical package/area name, lowercase
       - subject: imperative present, ≤ 72 chars, no trailing
         period (e.g. "align CLI examples with current flags")
       - full_message: type(scope): subject — plus an optional
         body summarising what was aligned. The body MUST end
         with the trailer line `Bot: docs-refresh` on its own line
         (after a blank line). This makes auto-commits
         identifiable via `git log --grep "^Bot: docs-refresh"` for
         post-run analysis (cost telemetry, revert tracking) —
         the v0.10 telemetry hook.
       - files: exact list of repo-relative paths to stage
       - committed: false (the tool will set this on its own
         output)

  ─── Findings handoff ─────────────────────────────────────

  After the structured commit output, you have ONE more job:
  capture anything you noticed during this run that is OUT OF
  SCOPE for doc alignment but worth surfacing to the next
  Nexie session.

  Examples to capture:
    - A code-level bug spotted while reading source for a
      doc-vs-code reconciliation.
    - An undocumented feature that needs its own ticket.
    - An infrastructure / sandbox issue you ran into.
    - A bot-prompt or workflow design improvement opportunity.

  What NOT to capture:
    - Doc drifts you just fixed (your commit covers them).
    - Style nits without an actionable next step.
    - Findings already on the board's `inbox` state — list
      them first (see step 1 below) to avoid duplicates.

  How:
    1. Call `mcp__iterion_board__list_issues` with
       `{ "state": "inbox" }` to see pending findings.
    2. For each NEW finding, call
       `mcp__iterion_board__create_issue` with:

           {
             "title": "One-line operator-facing summary",
             "body":  "Full context (file paths + suggested next step). 5-30 lines.",
             "state": "inbox",
             "labels": [
               "findings",
               "kind:bug",            // or drift | improvement | question
               "source:docs_refresh",
               "area:<subsystem>",
               "severity:<low|medium|high>"
             ]
           }

       Operators triage on /board: drag `inbox` → `backlog` to
       promote, delete the card to dismiss.

  Be conservative. Zero findings is fine.

prompt prepare_commit_user:
  Pick the files and produce the semantic commit name for the
  doc alignment fixes applied during this docs-refresh run.

  Workspace: {{vars.workspace_dir}}


## ─── Schemas ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## code_surface (v0.6.0): the inventory of "publicly-exposed"
## identifiers extracted from the workspace by the
## `scan_code_surface` tool. Reviewers receive these as a
## counter-omission audit list — for each identifier, verify it
## appears in at least one doc in scope. Mismatch_kind for missed
## items: `undocumented_capability`.
schema code_surface:
  cli_commands: string[]
  cli_flags: string[]
  diagnostic_codes: string[]
  scan_skipped: string

## scan_output is the immutable doc footprint emitted by the
## upstream scan_docs tool node. recently_changed_code_files is
## populated from `git diff` when vars.diff_since is set
## (otherwise empty array). bundle_self_path is echoed for
## transparency.
##
## v0.5.0 adds `pre_verified_docs`: docs whose content AND all
## referenced code-file SHAs match what was recorded in
## `.iterion/docs-refresh/audit-cache.json` after the previous
## successful run. These docs are seeded into
## `cumulative_audited_docs` from iter 0, lifting the coverage
## gate immediately for unchanged regions. Reviewers focus on
## `doc_files - pre_verified_docs`.
schema scan_output:
  doc_files: string[]
  doc_count: int
  ## DEFAULT-CREATE gate (v0.3.0): true when doc_count == 0 (no docs in
  ## scope). Routes scan_docs -> author_docs (bootstrap an initial doc
  ## set) instead of straight into the review loop. After authoring, the
  ## run re-scans; no_docs is then false and the normal path runs.
  no_docs: bool
  footprint_hash: string
  scope_globs: string[]
  recently_changed_code_files: string[]
  bundle_self_path: string
  pre_verified_docs: string[]
  cache_hits: int
  cache_misses: int

## review_input v0.15.0: manifest-driven shape. Replaces the
## v0.2.0 doc_files / pre_verified_docs / cli_commands / ... bulk
## with the bounded drift_candidates set from build_manifest plus
## the summary stats the gates need. Cross-family pushback +
## chronic-path signals carry through unchanged.
schema review_input:
  ## Deterministic manifest summary (build_manifest outputs)
  total_docs: int
  total_anchors: int
  verified_anchors: int
  drifted_anchors: int
  unverifiable_anchors: int
  manifest_coverage_pct: int
  ## Working set for this iteration (bounded by vars.max_drift_candidates).
  ## Each entry: {doc, line, kind, value, status, evidence, excerpt}.
  drift_candidates: json
  ## Full per-doc breakdown — telemetry / reports surface (NOT
  ## sized-bounded; ~doc_count entries with 3 ints each).
  per_doc_anchor_counts: json
  ## Mechanical coverage trail: every doc the manifest scanned.
  ## Supersedes the v0.14.0 previous_audited_docs[] pattern — the
  ## manifest IS coverage; reviewers no longer claim it.
  all_audited_docs: string[]

  ## v0.16.0 chunking visibility. Reviewers see the chunk dimension
  ## so they understand why some drifts may not be in this slice —
  ## they will surface in a later iter as the fixer clears earlier
  ## chunks. Coverage gate is still anchor-level across ALL docs,
  ## so chunking does not let the workflow terminate early.
  docs_with_drift_count: int
  chunked: bool
  chunk_doc_count: int
  max_review_chunk_docs: int

  ## Convergence threshold (vars.coverage_target_pct passthrough)
  coverage_target_pct: int

  ## Cross-family iteration context
  prior_pushback: string[]
  prior_pushback_justification: string
  prior_code_files_touched_claude: string[]
  prior_code_files_touched_gpt: string[]

  ## v0.13.0 scope-honesty gate input.
  ## cumulative_chronic_paths: the deduplicated list of paths the
  ## enforce_fix_scope tool has had to revert ≥3 times across the
  ## run so far. EMPTY by default — the threshold is computed
  ## inside enforce_fix_scope from the cumulative history, and
  ## streak_check accumulates only paths that have crossed the
  ## threshold. The raw revert history is INTENTIONALLY hidden
  ## from the reviewer: v0.12 exposed it and the reviewer over-
  ## reacted at threshold=1-2 via inline hints, defeating the
  ## strict-threshold design.
  cumulative_chronic_paths: string[]

  ## v0.17.0 do-not-relitigate inputs. The deduplicated unions of
  ## (a) every `audited_pairs` element from a prior reviewer that
  ## raised ZERO blockers on its iteration (i.e. the
  ## cross-family-confirmed not-drift items), and (b) every blocker
  ## the fixer pushed back across both families. Reviewers must
  ## dismiss items in these lists on sight unless they have NEW
  ## evidence — re-judging settled items is the oscillation
  ## driver that drove the 2026-06-23 dogfood past its iteration
  ## ceiling. Empty on iter 0.
  cumulative_dismissed_pairs: string[]
  cumulative_pushback: string[]

## verdict_output: the blockers field stays JSON (DSL schema
## parser doesn't support nested object arrays). The per-blocker
## fields incl. the `anchor_kind` enum are documented in
## skills/doc-mismatch-taxonomy.md and enforced at the prompt
## level.
##
## blocker_count (v0.3.0): the explicit count of items the agent
## put into `blockers`. Necessary because iterion's expr
## `length()` on a json field returns the JSON-encoded string's
## char count, not the array's item count, so the streak gate
## couldn't reliably distinguish "0 blockers" from "10 blockers".
## With this explicit field the streak gate can fire when both
## reviewers report blocker_count=0 even when one of them only
## soft-rejected (confidence: low) — the v0.2.0 dogfood deadlocked
## in exactly that state after GPT had exhausted productive
## audit surfaces but kept voting `approved: false` with
## `confidence: low`.
schema verdict_output:
  approved: bool
  family: string [enum: "claude", "gpt"]
  blockers: json
  blocker_count: int
  fix_plan: string
  confidence: string [enum: "low", "medium", "high"]
  audited_pairs: string[]
  audited_docs: string[]
  escalate_to_human: bool

## streak_state: now includes the file-level cumulative coverage
## tracker (cumulative_audited_docs) and the mechanically
## computed coverage_pct. The `stop` field embeds the coverage
## gate.
schema streak_state:
  stop: bool
  approved: bool
  family: string
  blockers: json
  blocker_count: int
  fix_plan: string
  ## v0.17.0: surface the current reviewer's `confidence` so the
  ## NEXT iteration's reviewer (cross-family) sees it via
  ## `loop.review_loop.previous_output.confidence` and can
  ## calibrate "verdicts must trend monotonically" (high-conf
  ## rejection followed by a fix should expect ≤N residual
  ## blockers; intuition-level low-conf is non-blocking).
  confidence: string
  cumulative_audited_pairs: string[]
  cumulative_audited_docs: string[]
  coverage_pct: int
  ## v0.17.0 do-not-relitigate accumulators.
  ## cumulative_dismissed_pairs: union of `audited_pairs` from
  ## every reviewer iteration whose `blocker_count == 0` — the
  ## set of doc::value pairs cross-family confirmed not-drift.
  ## cumulative_pushback: union of every fixer pushback string
  ## across both families. Both feed the next reviewer's
  ## "do NOT re-raise without new evidence" gate.
  cumulative_dismissed_pairs: string[]
  cumulative_pushback: string[]
  ## v0.12.0: every path the enforce_fix_scope tool had to revert
  ## this run (with duplicates). Kept for telemetry — feeds
  ## enforce_fix_scope's own threshold computation on each iter
  ## via the fix→enforce edge, and exposed in events/reports
  ## for post-run debugging. NOT passed to the reviewer (v0.13).
  cumulative_reverted_paths: string[]
  ## v0.13.0: deduplicated list of paths that have crossed the
  ## ≥3-revert chronic threshold. Computed inside enforce_fix_scope
  ## each iter, accumulated here, and exposed to the reviewer as
  ## the SOLE scope-honesty signal. Empty until any path has been
  ## reverted 3+ times.
  cumulative_chronic_paths: string[]
  ## v0.14.0: deduplicated union of every per-iter `declared_paths`
  ## fed into enforce_fix_scope across the run. Wired back into
  ## enforce_fix_scope as `cumulative_so_far_declared` so prior
  ## iters' kept files survive subsequent iters whose declared set
  ## understandably narrows to the new fix blockers. Without this,
  ## iter 2's git-diff baseline includes iter 1's keepers and they
  ## all get reverted as "undeclared" — observed during the
  ## 2026-05-21 dogfood (issue e79d91c7).
  cumulative_declared_paths: string[]

schema fix_input:
  blockers: json
  fix_plan: string

schema fix_output:
  applied: bool
  summary: string
  modified_doc_files: string[]
  code_files_touched: string[]
  pushback: string[]
  pushback_justification: string

## DEFAULT-CREATE (v0.3.0) schemas. author_docs bootstraps an initial
## documentation set when a repo has none. Its OUTPUT is observational
## only: the run re-scans the filesystem afterward (scan_docs re-globs),
## so nothing downstream consumes these fields — the schema exists to
## make the node DSL-valid and to surface what was authored in reports.
schema author_input:
  workspace_dir: string
  docs_dir: string
  recently_changed_code_files: string[]

schema author_output:
  docs_created: bool
  created_doc_files: string[]
  summary: string

## Commit-phase schemas.
schema commit_output:
  type: string [enum: "docs", "fix"]
  scope: string
  subject: string
  full_message: string
  files: string[]
  committed: bool

schema commit_tool_input:
  full_message: string
  files: string[]
  workspace_dir: string

schema commit_result:
  success: bool
  output: string

## v0.15.4: schema for mark_issue_for_review's free-form output.
## The tool returns JSON-as-string on success ({"id":...,"state":...})
## or {"skipped":"no issue_id"} on the manual-CLI no-op path. We
## don't consume the value downstream — the schema exists to make
## the tool node DSL-valid.
schema mark_issue_output:
  text: string

## update_audit_cache I/O (v0.5.0). The `audited_pairs: string[]`
## field is shell-tokenised by iterion's template substitution
## (`'pair1' 'pair2' 'pair3'`) so each element lands as a separate
## argv entry to python3 — env var passing breaks on internal
## whitespace, JSON encoding is unreachable via the {{!...}} raw
## form because raw values still go through env-var assignment.
schema update_audit_cache_input:
  workspace_dir: string
  cache_path: string
  audited_pairs: string[]

schema update_audit_cache_output:
  cache_path: string
  entries_written: int
  skipped: string

schema detect_changes_output:
  has_changes: bool

## enforce_fix_scope I/O (v0.11.0). The fixer DECLARES the files
## it modified via `fix_output.modified_doc_files`; this tool
## walks `git diff --name-only` against that declaration and
## reverts any out-of-declaration change so the fixer can't
## silently edit files outside its writeable set. Catches the
## v0.10 dogfood gap where fix_gpt edited the bot's own skill
## despite scan_docs excluding it via bundle_self_path.
schema enforce_fix_scope_input:
  workspace_dir: string
  declared_paths: string[]
  ## v0.13.0: the full revert history from streak_check so the
  ## tool can compute per-path counts AT THIS ITERATION and emit
  ## `chronic_paths` itself — keeps the threshold logic in
  ## deterministic-tool land rather than in expression DSL.
  cumulative_so_far: string[]
  ## v0.14.0: deduplicated union of every prior iter's declared
  ## paths. The tool keeps any file in this set even when the
  ## current iter doesn't redeclare it, so iter N can declare just
  ## the new blockers it fixed without sacrificing iter N-1's
  ## kept work to the baseline-relative `git diff --name-only`.
  cumulative_so_far_declared: string[]

## build_manifest I/O (v0.15.0 — manifest-driven reviewers).
##
## Replaces the ad-hoc "reviewer greps everything" pattern with a
## deterministic anchor extraction + verification pass. For each
## doc in the footprint, scans for code references (file paths,
## symbols, CLI commands, CLI flags, diagnostic codes, markdown
## link targets), then checks each anchor against the live code
## state (scan_code_surface outputs + filesystem). The reviewer
## then audits ONLY the drift candidates — a bounded set with
## pre-fetched evidence — instead of grepping the workspace itself.
##
## The before/after on the 2026-05-21 dogfood: reviewer_gpt's iter
## 1 burned through 4 LLM steps and ~400K input tokens enumerating
## anchors via grep before hitting context_length_exceeded. Under
## the manifest pattern, the same iter receives ~150 pre-resolved
## candidates with file:line evidence — bounded context, ~5 tool
## steps to spot-check the high-severity ones, structured verdict.
schema build_manifest_input:
  workspace_dir: string
  doc_files: string[]
  cli_commands: string[]
  cli_flags: string[]
  diagnostic_codes: string[]
  code_scope_globs: string
  ## max_drift_candidates caps the drift_candidates[] slice so the
  ## reviewer's prompt stays bounded regardless of how degraded the
  ## docs are. The full counts are still reported in the summary
  ## fields for the streak gate.
  max_drift_candidates: int
  ## v0.16.0: max distinct docs whose candidates may appear in a
  ## single chunk. Applied after the severity sort, before the
  ## max_drift_candidates cap. 0 disables doc-chunking.
  max_review_chunk_docs: int

schema build_manifest_output:
  ## total_docs / total_anchors are the cardinality of the
  ## deterministic enumeration. Per-doc breakdown lives in
  ## per_doc_anchor_counts (bounded by doc count, not anchor count).
  total_docs: int
  total_anchors: int
  ## verified_anchors counts anchors whose existence/presence the
  ## tool confirmed mechanically (file exists, CLI command in
  ## scan_code_surface output, diagnostic code present, etc.).
  ## drifted_anchors = total - verified - unverifiable.
  verified_anchors: int
  drifted_anchors: int
  unverifiable_anchors: int
  ## checkable_anchors = verified + drifted (excludes unverifiable).
  ## coverage_pct = verified / checkable, so anchors whose scanner was
  ## skipped/unscoped don't drag the gate below reach.
  checkable_anchors: int
  coverage_pct: int
  ## drift_candidates is the reviewer's working set. Each entry
  ## carries the doc::anchor pair plus pre-fetched evidence so the
  ## reviewer can judge "real drift vs false positive" without
  ## running its own grep loop. Capped at input.max_drift_candidates;
  ## when more candidates exist, the entries are prioritised by
  ## severity (removed/drifted CLI surface > drifted file_ref >
  ## unverifiable symbol).
  drift_candidates: json
  ## per_doc_anchor_counts is the deterministic coverage signal —
  ## each entry says "doc X had Y anchors total, Z of them verified".
  ## streak_check picks coverage_pct from the summary; this list
  ## exists for telemetry / reports.
  per_doc_anchor_counts: json
  ## all_audited_docs lists every doc the manifest scanned. The
  ## reviewer no longer claims coverage via its own audited_docs[]
  ## — the manifest pass IS the audit. streak_check pulls this
  ## list into its cumulative_audited_docs.
  all_audited_docs: string[]
  ## v0.16.0 doc-count chunking telemetry. `docs_with_drift_count`
  ## is the universe of docs that still have at least one drift
  ## candidate this iter (before chunking). `chunk_doc_count` is
  ## the count of distinct docs whose candidates landed in this
  ## iter's slice. `chunked=true` when chunk_doc_count <
  ## docs_with_drift_count (some docs deferred to a later iter).
  ## `max_review_chunk_docs` echoes the var so the reviewer prompt
  ## can show the operator the active cap.
  docs_with_drift_count: int
  chunked: bool
  chunk_doc_count: int
  max_review_chunk_docs: int

schema enforce_fix_scope_output:
  reverted_paths: string[]
  kept_paths: int
  declared_count: int
  changed_count: int
  ## v0.13.0: paths that, after folding THIS iter's reverts into
  ## the prior cumulative_so_far history, have been reverted ≥3
  ## times. Deduplicated. Empty until any path crosses the
  ## threshold. Routed through streak_check.cumulative_chronic_paths
  ## to the next reviewer's input.
  chronic_paths: string[]
  ## v0.14.0: echo of the CURRENT iter's declared_paths. Routed
  ## through streak_check.cumulative_declared_paths so the next
  ## iter's enforce_fix_scope can union it into the keep-set.
  declared_iter: string[]


## ─── Nodes ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

## scan_docs runs ONCE upstream of the review loop. Emits the
## immutable doc footprint + (when vars.diff_since is set) the
## list of code files changed since that ref. Auto-excludes the
## bot's own bundle via vars.bundle_self_path (fix 4).
##
## Raw-string command — the python snippet embeds quotes and the
## raw-string form avoids escape hell. Templates {{vars.X}}
## resolve at iterion's command-substitution layer; the values
## are then exposed to python via shell env vars (WS, GLOBS,
## BUNDLE_SELF, DIFF_SINCE).
tool scan_docs:
  command: `WS={{vars.workspace_dir}} GLOBS={{vars.doc_globs}} BUNDLE_SELF={{vars.bundle_self_path}} DIFF_SINCE={{vars.diff_since}} CACHE_PATH={{vars.audit_cache_path}} EXCLUDED_DIRS={{vars.excluded_dirs}} python3 -c "
import os, json, glob, hashlib, subprocess
ws = os.environ['WS']
globs = [g.strip() for g in os.environ['GLOBS'].split(',') if g.strip()]
bundle_self = os.environ.get('BUNDLE_SELF', '').strip().rstrip(os.sep)
diff_since = os.environ.get('DIFF_SINCE', '').strip()
cache_path = os.environ.get('CACHE_PATH', '').strip()
os.chdir(ws)
EXCLUDE_DIRS = {d.strip() for d in os.environ.get('EXCLUDED_DIRS', '').split(',') if d.strip()}
def excluded(p):
    if any(part in EXCLUDE_DIRS for part in p.split(os.sep)):
        return True
    if bundle_self and (p == bundle_self or p.startswith(bundle_self + os.sep)):
        return True
    return False
def sha_of_file(p):
    try:
        with open(p, 'rb') as fh:
            return hashlib.sha1(fh.read()).hexdigest()
    except (FileNotFoundError, IsADirectoryError, PermissionError):
        return 'missing'
files = sorted({f for g in globs for f in glob.glob(g, recursive=True) if os.path.isfile(f) and not excluded(f)})
h = hashlib.sha1(chr(10).join(files).encode()).hexdigest()
recent = []
if diff_since:
    try:
        proc = subprocess.run(['git', 'diff', '--name-only', diff_since + '...HEAD'], capture_output=True, text=True, check=True)
        recent = sorted([l for l in proc.stdout.splitlines() if l and not excluded(l)])
    except Exception:
        recent = []
pre_verified = []
hits = 0
misses = 0
if cache_path:
    try:
        with open(cache_path) as cf:
            cache = json.load(cf)
        doc_entries = cache.get('doc', {})
        for doc_path in files:
            entry = doc_entries.get(doc_path)
            if not entry:
                misses += 1
                continue
            current_sha = sha_of_file(doc_path)
            if entry.get('sha') != current_sha:
                misses += 1
                continue
            refs_ok = True
            for ref in entry.get('refs', []):
                p = ref.get('p', '')
                s = ref.get('s', '')
                if not p:
                    continue
                current = sha_of_file(p) if os.path.exists(p) else 'missing'
                if current != s:
                    refs_ok = False
                    break
            if refs_ok:
                pre_verified.append(doc_path)
                hits += 1
            else:
                misses += 1
    except (FileNotFoundError, json.JSONDecodeError):
        pass
print(json.dumps({'doc_files': files, 'doc_count': len(files), 'no_docs': len(files) == 0, 'footprint_hash': h, 'scope_globs': globs, 'recently_changed_code_files': recent, 'bundle_self_path': bundle_self, 'pre_verified_docs': pre_verified, 'cache_hits': hits, 'cache_misses': misses}))
"`
  output: scan_output

## scan_code_surface (v0.6.0): runs after scan_docs and extracts
## "publicly-exposed identifiers" from the workspace via grep so
## reviewers can audit code→doc presence (the inverse direction
## of the existing doc→code audit). Categories:
##   - cli_commands: cobra `Use:` literals in cmd/iterion/*.go
##   - cli_flags: --flag-name tokens in StringVar/BoolVar/...Var
##     calls inside the same files
##   - diagnostic_codes: "Cxxx" constants in pkg/dsl/ir/*.go and
##     pkg/dsl/parser/*.go
##
## When `cli_surface_globs` AND `diagnostic_surface_globs` are
## both empty, the scan is skipped and the output is empty lists
## with scan_skipped set to a reason string. Useful for runs
## targeting docs that have no CLI / diagnostic surface (e.g.
## a library-only repo).
##
## OPT-IN, iterion-shaped SPECIALIZATION — not a universal default.
## The `cobra Use:` / `--flag` / `Cxxx` patterns below only yield
## meaningful output on a repo with iterion's own code shape, so this
## scanner ships OFF (both surface globs empty by default). A run
## against any other repo either leaves it skipped or points the globs
## at that repo's own surface patterns via --var. Generalising these
## regexes to another stack is the bar for making it a default. See
## CLAUDE.md "Catalog bots are repo-agnostic".
tool scan_code_surface:
  command: `WS={{vars.workspace_dir}} CLI_GLOBS={{vars.cli_surface_globs}} DIAG_GLOBS={{vars.diagnostic_surface_globs}} python3 -c "
import os, json, glob, re
ws = os.environ['WS']
cli_globs = [g.strip() for g in os.environ.get('CLI_GLOBS','').split(',') if g.strip()]
diag_globs = [g.strip() for g in os.environ.get('DIAG_GLOBS','').split(',') if g.strip()]
os.chdir(ws)
if not cli_globs and not diag_globs:
    print(json.dumps({'cli_commands': [], 'cli_flags': [], 'diagnostic_codes': [], 'scan_skipped': 'both globs empty'}))
    raise SystemExit(0)
cli_files = sorted({f for g in cli_globs for f in glob.glob(g, recursive=True) if os.path.isfile(f)})
diag_files = sorted({f for g in diag_globs for f in glob.glob(g, recursive=True) if os.path.isfile(f)})
## v0.15.3: Use: pattern allows optional [args] / <args> suffixes inside
## the quoted string (cobra convention for declaring positional args).
## Previously the regex required \" immediately after the captured name,
## so 'Use: \"dispatch [config.yaml]\"' didn't match and 'dispatch' was
## reported as a drifted CLI command on every iter.
cmd_re = re.compile(r'Use:\s*\"([a-zA-Z0-9_\-]+)(?:[\s<\[\{].*?)?\"')
## v0.15.3: two flag patterns:
##   - Var family: BoolVar(&ptr, \"name\", ...) — takes a pointer first
##   - Non-Var: cobra's Flags().String(\"name\", ...) without backing var
## Both with optional P suffix (StringP, BoolP) for shorthand variants.
## Previously the Non-Var family was unscanned, so 'paths' and 'format'
## (declared via Flags().StringSlice / Flags().String in cmd/iterion/
## bots.go) were reported as drifted on every iter. The negative
## lookahead (?!Get) excludes the read variants Flags().GetString etc.
flag_var_re = re.compile(r'(?:String|Bool|Int|Duration|Float64|Int64|StringSlice|StringArray)Var\(\s*&[a-zA-Z0-9_.]+\s*,\s*\"([a-zA-Z][a-zA-Z0-9-]*)\"')
flag_nonvar_re = re.compile(r'Flags\(\)\.(?!Get)(?:String|Bool|Int|Duration|Float64|Int64)(?:Slice|Array)?P?\(\s*\"([a-zA-Z][a-zA-Z0-9-]*)\"')
diag_const_re = re.compile(r'\"(C[0-9]{3})\"')
cli_commands = set()
cli_flags = set()
for path in cli_files:
    try:
        with open(path) as fh: src = fh.read()
    except: continue
    for m in cmd_re.finditer(src): cli_commands.add(m.group(1))
    for m in flag_var_re.finditer(src): cli_flags.add(m.group(1))
    for m in flag_nonvar_re.finditer(src): cli_flags.add(m.group(1))
diagnostic_codes = set()
for path in diag_files:
    try:
        with open(path) as fh: src = fh.read()
    except: continue
    for m in diag_const_re.finditer(src): diagnostic_codes.add(m.group(1))
print(json.dumps({
    'cli_commands': sorted(cli_commands),
    'cli_flags': sorted(cli_flags),
    'diagnostic_codes': sorted(diagnostic_codes),
    'scan_skipped': ''
}))
"`
  output: code_surface

## build_manifest (v0.15.0): deterministic anchor extraction +
## verification + evidence collection. Replaces the
## reviewer-side "grep everything" pattern.
##
## For each doc in input.doc_files, scans the markdown and
## extracts code anchors via regex:
##   - file_ref      — paths like `pkg/foo/bar.go`, `docs/dsl.md`,
##                     `cmd/iterion/run.go:42` (with optional line
##                     suffix)
##   - cli_command   — backtick-quoted `iterion <subcmd>` invocations
##                     matching scan_code_surface.cli_commands
##   - cli_flag      — `--flag-name` mentions in inline code spans
##   - diagnostic    — `CNNN` codes referenced in prose
##   - symbol_ref    — backtick-quoted Go-style identifiers
##                     (`PackageName.TypeName` or `FunctionName`)
##                     that look like exported symbols
##
## Each anchor is then verified:
##   - file_ref     → does the file exist on disk?
##   - cli_command  → is it in input.cli_commands?
##   - cli_flag     → is it in input.cli_flags?
##   - diagnostic   → is it in input.diagnostic_codes?
##   - symbol_ref   → does `git grep -l` find it in code_scope_globs?
##
## Drift candidates = anchors whose verification failed. Each
## carries pre-fetched evidence (the doc line excerpt + the
## verifier's miss reason) so the reviewer can judge semantics
## without running its own grep loop. Output is bounded:
## input.max_drift_candidates caps the candidate slice; the full
## counts ride along in the summary fields for the streak gate.
##
## All inputs flow via env vars (JSON-encoded for arrays); the
## tool's argv is empty.
tool build_manifest:
  command: `WS={{input.workspace_dir}} DOC_FILES='{{!input.doc_files}}' CLI_COMMANDS='{{!input.cli_commands}}' CLI_FLAGS='{{!input.cli_flags}}' DIAG_CODES='{{!input.diagnostic_codes}}' CODE_GLOBS={{input.code_scope_globs}} MAX_CANDIDATES={{input.max_drift_candidates}} MAX_CHUNK_DOCS={{input.max_review_chunk_docs}} python3 -c "
import os, json, re, glob, subprocess
ws = os.environ['WS']
os.chdir(ws)
def jload(name, default):
    raw = os.environ.get(name, '')
    if not raw:
        return default
    try:
        return json.loads(raw)
    except json.JSONDecodeError:
        return default
doc_files = jload('DOC_FILES', [])
cli_commands = set(jload('CLI_COMMANDS', []))
cli_flags = set(jload('CLI_FLAGS', []))
diag_codes = set(jload('DIAG_CODES', []))
code_globs = [g.strip() for g in os.environ.get('CODE_GLOBS', '').split(',') if g.strip()]
try:
    max_candidates = int(os.environ.get('MAX_CANDIDATES', '150'))
except ValueError:
    max_candidates = 150
try:
    max_chunk_docs = int(os.environ.get('MAX_CHUNK_DOCS', '0'))
except ValueError:
    max_chunk_docs = 0

## Regexes targeting markdown-typical patterns.
## file_ref: paths like pkg/foo/bar.go, docs/dsl.md, with optional :NN line.
## We restrict to known code/doc roots to avoid false hits on prose.
## (?<![./\w-]) instead of \b: \b matched the /→letter boundary INSIDE a
## longer path (e.g. '.archive/examples/foo.iter' captured 'examples/foo.iter',
## silently dropping the '.archive/' prefix → phantom file-not-found drift).
## The lookbehind refuses to start a match mid-path, so a known-root token is
## only captured when it's the true start of the reference.
FILE_RE = re.compile(r'(?<![./\w-])((?:pkg|cmd|internal|examples|docs|scripts|studio|.github|sdks)/[A-Za-z0-9_./-]+\.(?:go|md|ts|tsx|py|sh|yaml|yml|json|bot|iter))(?::([0-9]+(?:-[0-9]+)?))?')
## chr(96) = backtick. The iterion DSL uses backticks as the raw-string
## delimiter for tool commands, so any literal backtick inside the
## command body (e.g. an inline-code regex) terminates the string and
## breaks the parser. Building the pattern at runtime via chr() dodges
## the conflict without forcing a different command-string syntax.
BT = chr(96)
## cli_command: backtick-quoted 'iterion <subcmd>' (subcmd is 1st word after iterion)
CLI_CMD_RE = re.compile(BT + r'iterion\s+([a-zA-Z0-9_-]+)')
## cli_flag: --kebab-flag tokens (allow leading backtick, allow trailing =)
CLI_FLAG_RE = re.compile(r'(?:\\s|^|' + BT + r'|\\()--([a-zA-Z][a-zA-Z0-9-]*[a-zA-Z0-9])\b')
## diag_code: literal CNNN with a 3-digit suffix.
DIAG_RE = re.compile(r'\b(C[0-9]{3})\b')
## symbol_ref: backtick-quoted CamelCase or pkg.Symbol identifiers.
## Strict pattern to avoid catching random capitalized words in prose.
SYM_RE = re.compile(BT + r'((?:[a-z][a-zA-Z0-9_]*\.)?[A-Z][A-Za-z0-9_]+(?:\.[A-Z][A-Za-z0-9_]+)?)' + BT)

def excerpt(line_text, limit=140):
    s = line_text.strip()
    return s if len(s) <= limit else s[:limit] + '…'

## md_link (v0.16.x): internal markdown links [text](path#anchor).
## FILE_RE only matches prose paths under known roots and never the
## #anchor fragment, so a dead doc-to-doc link or a broken heading
## anchor (e.g. CLAUDE.md -> README.md#iter-vs-bot) slipped through the
## whole audit. This captures the link URL (first token after '(',
## stopping at whitespace so an optional "title" is ignored without
## needing a literal double-quote in this backtick command body) and
## verifies BOTH the target file's existence AND, for .md targets, the
## heading anchor — slugified GitHub-style. dead_link is already in the
## reviewer taxonomy; this feeds it deterministic candidates.
MD_LINK_RE = re.compile(r'\[(?:[^\]]*)\]\(([^)\s]+)')
_heading_cache = {}
def slugify(text):
    s = text.strip().lower().replace(BT, '')
    s = re.sub(r'[^\w\s-]', '', s)
    s = re.sub(r'\s', '-', s)
    return s.strip('-')
def headings_of(path):
    if path in _heading_cache:
        return _heading_cache[path]
    slugs = set()
    try:
        with open(path, encoding='utf-8', errors='replace') as fh:
            for ln in fh:
                hm = re.match(r'\s{0,3}(#{1,6})\s+(.+)', ln)
                if hm:
                    slugs.add(slugify(hm.group(2)))
    except (FileNotFoundError, IsADirectoryError, PermissionError):
        pass
    _heading_cache[path] = slugs
    return slugs

anchors = []
per_doc_counts = {}
for doc in doc_files:
    try:
        with open(doc, encoding='utf-8', errors='replace') as fh:
            lines = fh.readlines()
    except (FileNotFoundError, IsADirectoryError, PermissionError):
        per_doc_counts[doc] = {'total': 0, 'verified': 0}
        continue
    seen_in_doc = set()
    doc_anchors = []
    for lineno, line in enumerate(lines, start=1):
        for m in FILE_RE.finditer(line):
            value = m.group(1)
            key = ('file_ref', value)
            if key in seen_in_doc:
                continue
            seen_in_doc.add(key)
            doc_anchors.append({'doc': doc, 'line': lineno, 'kind': 'file_ref', 'value': value, 'excerpt': excerpt(line)})
        for m in CLI_CMD_RE.finditer(line):
            value = m.group(1)
            key = ('cli_command', value)
            if key in seen_in_doc:
                continue
            seen_in_doc.add(key)
            doc_anchors.append({'doc': doc, 'line': lineno, 'kind': 'cli_command', 'value': value, 'excerpt': excerpt(line)})
        for m in CLI_FLAG_RE.finditer(line):
            value = m.group(1)
            key = ('cli_flag', value)
            if key in seen_in_doc:
                continue
            seen_in_doc.add(key)
            doc_anchors.append({'doc': doc, 'line': lineno, 'kind': 'cli_flag', 'value': value, 'excerpt': excerpt(line)})
        for m in DIAG_RE.finditer(line):
            value = m.group(1)
            key = ('diagnostic', value)
            if key in seen_in_doc:
                continue
            seen_in_doc.add(key)
            doc_anchors.append({'doc': doc, 'line': lineno, 'kind': 'diagnostic', 'value': value, 'excerpt': excerpt(line)})
        for m in SYM_RE.finditer(line):
            value = m.group(1)
            ## Skip obvious markdown headings / English words. A heuristic:
            ## must contain at least one of [A-Z][a-z]+[A-Z] (CamelCase),
            ## OR a dot (pkg.Symbol).
            if not (re.search(r'[A-Z][a-z]+[A-Z]', value) or '.' in value):
                continue
            key = ('symbol_ref', value)
            if key in seen_in_doc:
                continue
            seen_in_doc.add(key)
            doc_anchors.append({'doc': doc, 'line': lineno, 'kind': 'symbol_ref', 'value': value, 'excerpt': excerpt(line)})
        for m in MD_LINK_RE.finditer(line):
            target = m.group(1)
            same_doc = target.startswith('#')
            if not same_doc and (re.match(r'^[a-z][a-z0-9+.-]*://', target) or target.startswith(('mailto:', 'tel:', '//', 'www.'))):
                continue
            if '#' in target:
                path_part, frag = target.split('#', 1)
            else:
                path_part, frag = target, ''
            key = ('md_link', target)
            if key in seen_in_doc:
                continue
            seen_in_doc.add(key)
            doc_anchors.append({'doc': doc, 'line': lineno, 'kind': 'md_link', 'value': target, 'path_part': path_part, 'frag': frag, 'excerpt': excerpt(line)})
    anchors.extend(doc_anchors)
    per_doc_counts[doc] = {'total': len(doc_anchors), 'verified': 0}

## Verification pass.
## Symbol lookups are deferred to a single git grep batch — cheaper
## than O(N) shell calls. Build the union of distinct symbols first.
symbols_to_check = sorted({a['value'] for a in anchors if a['kind'] == 'symbol_ref'})
present_symbols = set()
if symbols_to_check and code_globs:
    ## git grep -l with alternation; chunk to avoid argv overflow.
    chunk_size = 100
    for i in range(0, len(symbols_to_check), chunk_size):
        chunk = symbols_to_check[i:i+chunk_size]
        pat = r'\b(' + '|'.join(re.escape(s.split('.')[-1]) for s in chunk) + r')\b'
        try:
            r = subprocess.run(['git', 'grep', '-lE', pat, '--'] + code_globs, capture_output=True, text=True, check=False)
            if r.returncode in (0, 1):
                ## We can only confirm at-least-one-match for the chunk
                ## as a whole; for per-symbol granularity we'd need
                ## N grep calls. Instead, do a content check: for each
                ## symbol in the chunk, regrep its leaf identifier in
                ## the union of matched files.
                matched_files = [l for l in r.stdout.splitlines() if l]
                if matched_files:
                    for sym in chunk:
                        leaf = sym.split('.')[-1]
                        try:
                            rr = subprocess.run(['git', 'grep', '-lE', r'\b' + re.escape(leaf) + r'\b', '--'] + matched_files, capture_output=True, text=True, check=False)
                            if rr.returncode == 0 and rr.stdout.strip():
                                present_symbols.add(sym)
                        except Exception:
                            pass
        except Exception:
            pass

verified = []
drifted = []
unverifiable = []
for a in anchors:
    k = a['kind']
    v = a['value']
    if k == 'file_ref':
        if os.path.exists(v):
            a['status'] = 'verified'
            a['evidence'] = 'file exists'
            verified.append(a)
        else:
            a['status'] = 'drifted'
            a['evidence'] = 'file not found on disk'
            drifted.append(a)
    elif k == 'cli_command':
        ## When scan_code_surface was skipped/unscoped, cli_commands is
        ## empty -- we never scanned the CLI surface, so we cannot call a
        ## doc's iterion-subcommand reference drifted-from-code. Treat as
        ## unverifiable (excluded from the coverage denominator) rather
        ## than emitting a false drift for every existing command.
        if not cli_commands:
            a['status'] = 'unverifiable'
            a['evidence'] = 'cli surface not scanned (scan skipped / code_scope_globs unscoped) — cannot adjudicate'
            unverifiable.append(a)
        elif v in cli_commands:
            a['status'] = 'verified'
            a['evidence'] = 'present in scan_code_surface.cli_commands'
            verified.append(a)
        else:
            a['status'] = 'drifted'
            a['evidence'] = 'not in scan_code_surface.cli_commands'
            drifted.append(a)
    elif k == 'cli_flag':
        if not cli_flags:
            a['status'] = 'unverifiable'
            a['evidence'] = 'cli surface not scanned (scan skipped / code_scope_globs unscoped) — cannot adjudicate'
            unverifiable.append(a)
        elif v in cli_flags:
            a['status'] = 'verified'
            a['evidence'] = 'present in scan_code_surface.cli_flags'
            verified.append(a)
        else:
            a['status'] = 'drifted'
            a['evidence'] = 'not in scan_code_surface.cli_flags'
            drifted.append(a)
    elif k == 'diagnostic':
        if not diag_codes:
            a['status'] = 'unverifiable'
            a['evidence'] = 'diagnostic surface not scanned (diagnostic_surface_globs unset) — cannot adjudicate'
            unverifiable.append(a)
        elif v in diag_codes:
            a['status'] = 'verified'
            a['evidence'] = 'present in scan_code_surface.diagnostic_codes'
            verified.append(a)
        else:
            a['status'] = 'drifted'
            a['evidence'] = 'not in scan_code_surface.diagnostic_codes'
            drifted.append(a)
    elif k == 'symbol_ref':
        if v in present_symbols:
            a['status'] = 'verified'
            a['evidence'] = 'matched in code_scope_globs'
            verified.append(a)
        else:
            ## Symbol heuristic is brittle (CamelCase prose, archived
            ## examples, …); treat misses as unverifiable rather than
            ## drifted to avoid Goodhart-trap blockers.
            a['status'] = 'unverifiable'
            a['evidence'] = 'no match in code_scope_globs (may be prose or external ref)'
            unverifiable.append(a)
    elif k == 'md_link':
        ## Internal markdown link: verify the target file exists, and for
        ## a .md target verify the #heading-anchor too (line anchors #Lnn
        ## are code-line refs, not headings — skip those). High precision:
        ## os.path.exists + GitHub-slug heading match. Misses are real dead
        ## links (objective, verifiable), so they are 'drifted', not the
        ## softer 'unverifiable' used for the brittle symbol heuristic.
        path_part = a.get('path_part', '')
        frag = a.get('frag', '')
        tgt = a['doc'] if not path_part else os.path.normpath(os.path.join(os.path.dirname(a['doc']), path_part))
        if path_part and not os.path.exists(tgt):
            a['status'] = 'drifted'
            a['evidence'] = 'link target not found: ' + tgt
            drifted.append(a)
        elif frag and not re.match(r'^[Ll][0-9]', frag) and tgt.endswith('.md'):
            if frag.lower() in headings_of(tgt):
                a['status'] = 'verified'
                a['evidence'] = 'anchor present in target'
                verified.append(a)
            else:
                a['status'] = 'drifted'
                a['evidence'] = 'dead anchor #' + frag + ' in ' + tgt
                drifted.append(a)
        else:
            a['status'] = 'verified'
            a['evidence'] = 'link target exists'
            verified.append(a)
    per_doc_counts[a['doc']]['verified'] += 1 if a['status'] == 'verified' else 0

## Prioritise candidates: drifted CLI surface first (highest signal),
## then drifted file_ref, then drifted diagnostic, then drifted symbol,
## then unverifiable symbols at the tail.
priority = {
    ('drifted', 'cli_command'): 0,
    ('drifted', 'cli_flag'): 0,
    ('drifted', 'md_link'): 1,
    ('drifted', 'diagnostic'): 1,
    ('drifted', 'file_ref'): 2,
    ('drifted', 'symbol_ref'): 3,
    ('unverifiable', 'symbol_ref'): 4,
}
## Surface drifted anchors plus unverifiable *symbol_ref*s (genuinely
## borderline — a reviewer may resolve them by reading code). Do NOT
## surface scanner-skipped cli/flag/diagnostic unverifiables: we know
## we never scanned that surface, so there is nothing for a reviewer to
## adjudicate — they would only be noise that tempts a false blocker.
candidates = drifted + [a for a in unverifiable if a['kind'] == 'symbol_ref']
candidates.sort(key=lambda a: (priority.get((a['status'], a['kind']), 9), a['doc'], a['line']))

## v0.16.0: doc-count chunking. After the severity sort, walk the
## ordered list and admit candidates from at most max_chunk_docs
## distinct docs. Once the doc budget is full, candidates from new
## docs are deferred (they surface in a later iter once the fixer
## clears earlier drifts). max_chunk_docs=0 disables chunking
## (preserves legacy candidate-cap-only behaviour).
docs_with_drift = sorted({a['doc'] for a in candidates})
if max_chunk_docs > 0 and len(docs_with_drift) > max_chunk_docs:
    chunk_docs = []
    chunked_candidates = []
    chunk_doc_set = set()
    for a in candidates:
        if a['doc'] in chunk_doc_set:
            chunked_candidates.append(a)
        elif len(chunk_doc_set) < max_chunk_docs:
            chunk_doc_set.add(a['doc'])
            chunk_docs.append(a['doc'])
            chunked_candidates.append(a)
    candidates = chunked_candidates
    chunked = True
else:
    chunked = False

if max_candidates > 0:
    candidates = candidates[:max_candidates]
chunk_doc_count = len({a['doc'] for a in candidates})

total_anchors = len(anchors)
verified_anchors = len(verified)
drifted_anchors = len(drifted)
unverifiable_anchors = len(unverifiable)
## Coverage is verified / (verified + drifted) — the fraction of
## MECHANICALLY-CHECKABLE anchors that verify. Unverifiable anchors
## (symbol-heuristic misses, and cli/flag/diagnostic anchors whose
## scanner was skipped/unscoped) are EXCLUDED from the denominator:
## counting them in the denominator dragged coverage below the gate
## every checkable claim was correct — e.g. 190 unverifiable / 907
## anchors capped achievable coverage at 79% < the 80% target, a
## permanent non-convergence deadlock. When nothing is checkable,
## coverage is vacuously complete (100) so the gate can still fire on
## reviewer approval instead of looping to exhaustion.
checkable_anchors = verified_anchors + drifted_anchors
coverage_pct = (verified_anchors * 100 // checkable_anchors) if checkable_anchors > 0 else 100

per_doc_list = sorted(
    [{'doc': d, 'total': c['total'], 'verified': c['verified']} for d, c in per_doc_counts.items()],
    key=lambda r: r['doc'],
)

print(json.dumps({
    'total_docs': len(doc_files),
    'total_anchors': total_anchors,
    'verified_anchors': verified_anchors,
    'drifted_anchors': drifted_anchors,
    'unverifiable_anchors': unverifiable_anchors,
    'checkable_anchors': checkable_anchors,
    'coverage_pct': coverage_pct,
    'drift_candidates': candidates,
    'per_doc_anchor_counts': per_doc_list,
    'all_audited_docs': sorted(doc_files),
    'docs_with_drift_count': len(docs_with_drift),
    'chunked': chunked,
    'chunk_doc_count': chunk_doc_count,
    'max_review_chunk_docs': max_chunk_docs,
}))
"`
  input: build_manifest_input
  output: build_manifest_output

router alt:
  mode: round_robin

judge reviewer_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-max}"
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_claude
  ## session: fresh for claude — the prompt cache hit comes from
  ## claude_code's automatic context reuse, not from explicit
  ## session inheritance, and a fresh session keeps each review
  ## an independent look (mirrors branch_improve_loop).
  session: fresh
  ## v0.15.0: tool_max_steps cap aligns reviewer_claude with the
  ## manifest pattern — the bounded drift_candidates list is in
  ## the prompt; spot-checks only.
  tool_max_steps: 25
  interaction: human

judge reviewer_gpt:
  ## Explicit backend pin: openai/gpt-5.5 only runs on claw.
  backend: "claw"
  model: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_MODEL_GPT:-openai/gpt-5.5}"
  ## Dropped from "high" to "medium" 2026-05-24: with the v0.15.0
  ## manifest pattern + the 80%-coverage doc set (89 docs / 175
  ## drift candidates), the gpt-5.5 reviewer running via the
  ## ChatGPT-forfait codex endpoint started hitting
  ## context_length_exceeded — the high-effort reasoning budget
  ## reserved enough tokens to blow the forfait's per-call cap
  ## (under the cap on the raw OpenAI API). Medium keeps the
  ## verdict quality while leaving headroom. Override with the
  ## env var when the input is small (e.g. branch-scoped audits).
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_EFFORT_GPT:-medium}"
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_gpt
  ## v0.7.0: session: inherit_if_available finally lands the cost
  ## optimisation that v0.2.0 attempted and had to revert. Plain
  ## `inherit` requires a non-empty `_session_id` from the edge —
  ## on iter 1 fix_gpt hasn't run, the template resolves to "",
  ## and the original v0.2.0 reading of the symptom blamed claw's
  ## OpenAI provider (it turned out to be insufficient_quota
  ## v0.15.0: with the manifest pattern, reviewer_gpt no longer
  ## enumerates anchors via tool calls — the bounded
  ## drift_candidates list is in the prompt. Spot-checks only.
  session: fresh
  ## claw builtin tools — read-only set, the reviewer NEVER writes.
  ## tool_max_steps dropped 20 → 10 (v0.15.0). Enumeration moved
  ## to the manifest tool; the budget covers spot-checks of the
  ## highest-stakes drifted CLI surface / diagnostic codes plus
  ## the final structured-output turn. 5 was too tight — the
  ## CLI counts each tool call as a turn and exhausted the budget
  ## before claude could emit JSON (error_max_turns observed).
  tools: [bash, read_file, glob, grep]
  tool_max_steps: 25
  interaction: human

## Deterministic streak detector + coverage gate.
##
## stop=true iff (cross-family double approval) AND (cumulative
## file-level coverage ≥ coverage_target_pct). The coverage_pct
## is `length(unique(prior + current audited_docs)) * 100 /
## doc_count`, guarded against doc_count=0 via `if(...)`. v0.1.0
## had no coverage gate; reviewer_claude iter 2 approved with
## ~13/51 audited and would have armed the streak.
##
## Soft-approval (low-confidence rejection) is passed through as
## approved for routing only — alternation continues without
## invoking the fixer, but stop still requires hard approvals.
## v0.3.0 streak_check changes vs v0.2.0:
##
## - `stop` now treats `blocker_count == 0` as effective approval
##   (regardless of `approved` / `confidence`). v0.2.0 deadlocked
##   when GPT consistently returned 0 blockers + confidence: low
##   after exhausting productive audit — `approved: false` blocked
##   the streak indefinitely even though both families agreed
##   nothing needed fixing.
##
## - `coverage_pct` is clamped to ≤ 100 via an inner `if()`.
##   Reviewers sometimes put paths into `audited_docs` that are
##   technically outside the original `doc_files` (e.g. a freshly
##   discovered doc, or an off-by-one path). Without clamping
##   that pushed coverage to 101+%, harmless for the gate
##   (>= 80%) but confusing in reports.
compute streak_check:
  output: streak_state
  expr:
    ## v0.15.0: coverage is now ANCHOR-level (manifest's
    ## verified/total ratio), not file-level (reviewer-claimed
    ## audited_docs union). The manifest scans every doc every
    ## iter, so coverage moves only when the fixer actually
    ## resolves drifts. No more reviewer-claimed coverage padding.
    ##
    ## v0.17.0 streak symmetry: the CURRENT side of `stop` now
    ## also launders low-confidence rejections, matching the
    ## previous side's laundering through `streak_state.approved`
    ## (which already folded in `input.confidence == 'low'` since
    ## v0.3.0). Pre-fix asymmetry — current side used raw
    ## `input.approved` while previous side used the laundered
    ## `previous_output.approved` — meant a CURRENT low-confidence
    ## rejection with non-zero blockers reset the streak that a
    ## PREVIOUS low-confidence rejection did not. Pure noise
    ## oscillated the gate. The asymptote requirement (CLAUDE.md
    ## "Review loops must converge to an asymptote") demands
    ## both sides treat low-conf identically.
    stop: "(input.approved || input.confidence == 'low' || input.blocker_count == 0) && (loop.review_loop.previous_output.approved || loop.review_loop.previous_output.blocker_count == 0) && input.family != loop.review_loop.previous_output.family && outputs.build_manifest.coverage_pct >= vars.coverage_target_pct"
    approved: "input.approved || input.confidence == 'low' || input.blocker_count == 0"
    family: "input.family"
    blockers: "input.blockers"
    blocker_count: "input.blocker_count"
    ## v0.17.0: carry the current reviewer's `confidence` into
    ## streak_state so the cross-family next iter sees it via
    ## `loop.review_loop.previous_output.confidence` and can
    ## reason about monotonic-trend (high-conf rejection then
    ## fix should expect ≤N residual blockers, etc.).
    confidence: "input.confidence"
    fix_plan: "input.fix_plan"
    cumulative_audited_pairs: "unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_audited_pairs, input.audited_pairs))"
    ## v0.17.0 do-not-relitigate accumulator: when the current
    ## reviewer raised ZERO blockers, EVERY pair in its
    ## audited_pairs is a cross-family-adjudicated not-drift item.
    ## Union it into the cumulative dismissed set so subsequent
    ## reviewers can dismiss those pairs on sight (the manifest
    ## re-emits the same candidates every iter; this is what
    ## stops re-judging them). When blockers > 0, no contribution
    ## (the reviewer DID raise issues on this iter; its
    ## audited_pairs contains both confirmed-drift and dismissed
    ## items intermixed and we cannot separate them in the DSL).
    cumulative_dismissed_pairs: "if(input.blocker_count == 0, unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_dismissed_pairs, input.audited_pairs)), outputs.streak_check.cumulative_dismissed_pairs)"
    ## v0.17.0 do-not-relitigate accumulator (fixer-side):
    ## union every fixer pushback across both families into the
    ## cumulative pushback set. Routed forward to both reviewers
    ## as `cumulative_pushback`. The reviewer rule: do NOT
    ## re-raise a previously-pushed-back blocker without new
    ## evidence rebutting the fixer's justification. The current
    ## iter's fixer pushback is the union of fix_claude.pushback
    ## + fix_gpt.pushback (whichever family fired most recently
    ## upstream of this reviewer; the union is idempotent under
    ## `unique`).
    cumulative_pushback: "unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_pushback, outputs.fix_claude.pushback, outputs.fix_gpt.pushback))"
    ## v0.15.0: file-level coverage is now the manifest's static
    ## all_audited_docs (every doc is mechanically scanned every
    ## iter). Kept on the schema for backward-compat in reports;
    ## the gate uses coverage_pct below instead.
    cumulative_audited_docs: "outputs.build_manifest.all_audited_docs"
    coverage_pct: "outputs.build_manifest.coverage_pct"
    ## v0.12.0: accumulate every enforce_fix_scope revert across
    ## the run, WITH duplicates. Kept for telemetry / events,
    ## and re-fed to enforce_fix_scope each iter so it can
    ## compute the per-path count and emit `chronic_paths`
    ## without re-counting in expr DSL. NOT exposed to reviewer
    ## in v0.13 — the reviewer only sees cumulative_chronic_paths.
    cumulative_reverted_paths: "concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_reverted_paths, input.enforce_reverted_paths)"
    ## v0.13.0: deduplicated accumulation of paths that have
    ## crossed the chronic threshold (≥3 reverts). Source of
    ## truth for the reviewer's SCOPE-HONESTY blocker. Once a
    ## path lands here it stays — the reviewer keeps surfacing
    ## the blocker until convergence.
    cumulative_chronic_paths: "unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_chronic_paths, input.enforce_chronic_paths))"
    ## v0.14.0: deduplicated union of every prior iter's
    ## declared_paths. Fed back into enforce_fix_scope so the
    ## keep-set widens across iterations instead of resetting to
    ## the new iter's narrow declaration. Without this, baseline-
    ## relative `git diff --name-only` flagged iter N-1's keepers
    ## as "undeclared" in iter N and reverted real work.
    cumulative_declared_paths: "unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_declared_paths, input.enforce_declared_iter))"

agent fix_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-max}"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  interaction: human

agent fix_gpt:
  backend: "claw"
  model: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_MODEL_GPT:-openai/gpt-5.5}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_EFFORT_GPT:-high}"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  tools: [bash, read_file, write_file, file_edit, glob, grep]
  tool_max_steps: 40
  interaction: human


## ─── Nodes : Default-create (author docs from zero) ─────────────

## DEFAULT-CREATE (v0.3.0): when scan_docs reports no_docs, this node
## bootstraps an initial documentation set from the code, then the run
## re-scans (author_rescan loop) so the normal review/refresh loop
## polishes + commits it. claude_code so it has the full native toolset
## to read the repo and write files; one-shot fresh session.
agent author_docs:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-max}"
  input: author_input
  output: author_output
  system: author_docs_system
  user: author_docs_user
  session: fresh
  interaction: human


## ─── Nodes : Commit ─────────────────────────────────────────────

agent prepare_commit:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_MODEL_CLAUDE:-claude-opus-4-8}"
  reasoning_effort: "${ITERION_DOC_ALIGN_EFFORT_CLAUDE:-max}"
  output: commit_output
  system: prepare_commit_system
  user: prepare_commit_user
  session: fresh
  readonly: true
  capabilities: [board.read, board.create]

tool commit_changes:
  command: "git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} add -- {{input.files}} && (git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} diff --cached --quiet || git -C {{input.workspace_dir}} commit -m {{input.full_message}})"
  input: commit_tool_input
  output: commit_result

## mark_issue_for_review (v0.15.4): after the run reaches a clean
## terminal state, transition the tracker issue out of `ready` so
## the dispatcher's polling loop doesn't re-dispatch it on the next
## tick (observed during run 019e4c2e: a no-op convergence walked
## the full workflow again on top of the previous commit, costing
## ~$1.50 per re-run for zero added signal).
##
## Skipped (no-op exit 0) when vars.issue_id is empty — manual CLI
## runs don't have a dispatcher-attached issue to transition.
##
## The store-dir is resolved relative to the worktree: the dispatcher
## puts the worktree at <host>/.iterion/dispatcher/workspaces/native_<id>/
## so three levels up lands on <host>/.iterion/ which is what
## `iterion issue move --store-dir` expects (the root that contains
## the `dispatcher/` subtree).
##
## v0.15.7: route through the dispatcher's HTTP API instead of
## the iterion CLI subprocess. The native store's in-memory index
## (pkg/dispatcher/native/store.go:s.index) is NOT invalidated
## when an external process writes the issue file — the dispatcher
## daemon's cached state survives the CLI's disk update and gets
## flushed back on the next Claim/Release, clobbering the move.
## Observed on the 2026-05-22 v0.15.6 dogfood (run 019e4e55):
## bot moved issue ready→review at 06:23:15, dispatcher's next
## Claim at 06:23:27 overwrote it back to ready without emitting
## an issue_state_changed event. The HTTP API path goes through
## the daemon's own Store instance, so the cache stays coherent.
##
## Port hardcoded to 4891 (the iterion studio default). If the
## studio is bound to a different port, override
## ITERION_DISPATCHER_PORT in the dispatcher's environment and
## tweak this command. Future iterion fix: expose dispatcher.port
## or dispatcher.url as a template var so this isn't hardcoded.
##
## ITERION_ISSUE_IDENTIFIER env var (set by the dispatcher per
## pkg/dispatcher/loop.go:450) carries the short issue id without
## the "native:" scheme prefix, which is exactly what the HTTP
## path needs: /api/v1/native/issues/{short-id}/transition.
##
## `|| true` keeps the workflow on the happy path if curl fails
## (network blip, daemon restart, etc.) — the commit has already
## landed.
tool mark_issue_for_review:
  command: `if [ -n {{vars.issue_id}} ]; then ID={{vars.issue_id}}; ID_SHORT=${ID#native:}; PORT=${ITERION_DISPATCHER_PORT:-4891}; curl -sS -X POST -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '{"to":"review"}' "http://localhost:${PORT}/api/v1/native/issues/${ID_SHORT}/transition" 2>&1 | head -c 1000 || true; else echo '{"skipped":"no issue_id"}'; fi`
  output: mark_issue_output

## enforce_fix_scope (v0.11.0): mechanical revert of any fix-stage
## edit outside the fixer's declared `modified_doc_files` set.
##
## Discovered during the v0.10 dogfood: fix_gpt edited
## `bots/docs-refresh/skills/doc-verification-checklist.md` —
## docs-refresh's own skill — despite scan_docs excluding it via
## `bundle_self_path`. The fixer's tool access (write_file,
## file_edit) is filesystem-wide; the skill-level constraint
## "you may not write outside doc_files" was unenforced.
##
## This node closes the gap mechanically: after every fix
## iteration, walk `git diff --name-only` and `git checkout --`
## anything that isn't in `input.declared_paths`. The fixer's
## own declaration is the contract — out-of-declaration edits
## are reverted before they reach the next reviewer.
##
## Emits `reverted_paths[]` for visibility; non-empty in events
## stream is the signal that the fixer needs prompt-side
## reinforcement (or the agent occasionally over-reaches).
tool enforce_fix_scope:
  ## v0.13.0: positional argv with a `--` sentinel between
  ## declared_paths and cumulative_so_far. iterion shell-tokenises
  ## string[] inputs into space-separated quoted tokens
  ## (`'a.md' 'b.md'`) so they land as separate argv entries —
  ## env-var passing collided (first token wins, rest become argv).
  ## v0.14.0: extended with a second sentinel `---` for the
  ## prior-iters' cumulative_so_far_declared union (so iter N-1's
  ## keepers don't get reverted in iter N's narrower scope).
  ## Layout: <ws> <declared...> -- <cumul_reverted...> --- <cumul_declared...>
  command: `python3 -c "
import os, json, subprocess, sys
from collections import Counter
args = sys.argv[1:]
ws = args[0] if args else ''
rest = args[1:]
try:
    i = rest.index('--')
    declared = set(rest[:i])
    after = rest[i+1:]
    try:
        j = after.index('---')
        cumulative_so_far = after[:j]
        cumulative_declared = set(after[j+1:])
    except ValueError:
        cumulative_so_far = after
        cumulative_declared = set()
except ValueError:
    declared = set(rest)
    cumulative_so_far = []
    cumulative_declared = set()
effective_declared = declared | cumulative_declared
os.chdir(ws)
try:
    proc = subprocess.run(['git', 'diff', '--name-only'], capture_output=True, text=True, check=True)
    changed = set(l for l in proc.stdout.splitlines() if l)
except Exception:
    changed = set()
out_of_scope = sorted(changed - effective_declared)
reverted = []
for path in out_of_scope:
    try:
        subprocess.run(['git', 'checkout', '--', path], check=True, capture_output=True)
        reverted.append(path)
    except subprocess.CalledProcessError:
        pass
counts = Counter(cumulative_so_far) + Counter(reverted)
chronic = sorted([p for p, c in counts.items() if c >= 3])
print(json.dumps({
    'reverted_paths': reverted,
    'kept_paths': len(changed) - len(reverted),
    'declared_count': len(declared),
    'changed_count': len(changed),
    'chronic_paths': chronic,
    'declared_iter': sorted(declared),
}))
" {{input.workspace_dir}} {{input.declared_paths}} -- {{input.cumulative_so_far}} --- {{input.cumulative_so_far_declared}}`
  input: enforce_fix_scope_input
  output: enforce_fix_scope_output

## update_audit_cache (v0.5.0): rewrites
## `<workspace_dir>/<audit_cache_path>` from the run's cumulative
## audited_pairs. Each pair `"<doc>::<anchor>"` contributes a
## reference entry; the anchor's path component is extracted with
## a permissive regex (everything up to the first `:`, space, or
## `(`). The current sha1 of each referenced path is captured so
## the NEXT run can pre-verify untouched (doc, refs) tuples.
##
## Empty cache_path disables the write — useful for one-shot CI
## runs that don't want to persist state.
##
## Runs after commit_changes so a failed commit doesn't poison
## the cache with audit data that wasn't actually shipped. The no-change
## path reaches it directly via detect_doc_changes (skipping the commit).

## EFFICIENCY guard (deterministic, no LLM). After the review streak
## converges, only spend the LLM prepare_commit + commit_changes when the
## fixers actually changed the working tree. A review-only convergence
## (no drift / nothing to fix) skips straight to the audit-cache refresh +
## done — so docs-refresh only pays the commit-prep turn when there is
## something to commit. Both unstaged and staged diffs are checked.
tool detect_doc_changes:
  command: `WS={{vars.workspace_dir}} CACHE={{vars.audit_cache_path}} python3 -c "
import os, subprocess, json
os.chdir(os.environ['WS'])
cache = os.environ.get('CACHE', '').strip()
# git status --porcelain reports BOTH tracked modifications AND untracked
# files (?? lines). Plain 'git diff' misses untracked — which is exactly
# the DEFAULT-CREATE case (author_docs writes brand-new, never-added .md
# files), so the commit step must still fire. Exclude the audit cache
# (written later / not a doc) so a stale cache file is not mistaken for
# doc work on a re-run.
lines = subprocess.run(['git', 'status', '--porcelain'], capture_output=True, text=True).stdout.splitlines()
sig = [l for l in lines if l.strip() and not (cache and l[3:].strip() == cache)]
print(json.dumps({'has_changes': len(sig) > 0}))
"`
  output: detect_changes_output

tool update_audit_cache:
  command: `python3 -c "
import os, json, hashlib, re, sys, pathlib
ws = sys.argv[1]
cache_path = sys.argv[2]
pairs = sys.argv[3:]
if not cache_path:
    print(json.dumps({'cache_path': '', 'entries_written': 0, 'skipped': 'no cache_path'}))
    sys.exit(0)
os.chdir(ws)
def sha_of_file(p):
    try:
        with open(p, 'rb') as fh:
            return hashlib.sha1(fh.read()).hexdigest()
    except (FileNotFoundError, IsADirectoryError, PermissionError):
        return 'missing'
def extract_path(anchor):
    a = (anchor or '').strip()
    if not a or a.startswith('<'):
        return None
    m = re.match(r'([^\s:()]+)', a)
    return m.group(1) if m else None
by_doc = {}
for pair in pairs:
    if not isinstance(pair, str) or '::' not in pair:
        continue
    doc, anchor = pair.split('::', 1)
    p = extract_path(anchor)
    if not p:
        continue
    by_doc.setdefault(doc, set()).add(p)
doc_entries = {}
for doc, refs in by_doc.items():
    doc_entries[doc] = {
        'sha': sha_of_file(doc),
        'refs': sorted(({'p': p, 's': sha_of_file(p) if os.path.exists(p) else 'missing'} for p in refs), key=lambda r: r['p']),
    }
out_path = pathlib.Path(cache_path)
out_path.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
with open(out_path, 'w') as out:
    json.dump({'v': 1, 'doc': doc_entries}, out, indent=2, sort_keys=True)
print(json.dumps({'cache_path': str(out_path), 'entries_written': len(doc_entries), 'skipped': ''}))
" {{input.workspace_dir}} {{input.cache_path}} {{input.audited_pairs}}`
  input: update_audit_cache_input
  output: update_audit_cache_output


## ─── Workflow ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

workflow docs_refresh:
  entry: scan_docs

  budget:
    max_parallel_branches: 1
    max_duration: "4h"
    max_cost_usd: 120

  compaction:
    threshold: 0.9
    preserve_recent: 8

  ## DEFAULT-CREATE (v0.3.0): if the repo has ZERO docs in scope,
  ## bootstrap an initial set first (author_docs), then loop back to
  ## scan_docs (author_rescan) so the re-scan picks the new docs up and
  ## the normal review/refresh loop polishes + commits them. Otherwise
  ## go straight to the review path. author_rescan(1) = exactly one
  ## authoring pass; if it still produces nothing in scope the bounded
  ## loop fails loudly (resumable) rather than spinning.
  scan_docs -> author_docs when no_docs with {
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}",
    docs_dir: "{{vars.docs_dir}}",
    recently_changed_code_files: "{{outputs.scan_docs.recently_changed_code_files}}"
  }
  scan_docs -> scan_code_surface when not no_docs
  author_docs -> scan_docs as author_rescan(1)

  ## v0.15.0: build_manifest runs after scan_code_surface (initial)
  ## AND after every enforce_fix_scope (loop re-entry), so the
  ## drift_candidates set the reviewers see always reflects the
  ## live worktree state. Both inbound edges supply identical
  ## with{} fields — the tool's input shape is the same regardless
  ## of which stage triggered it.
  scan_code_surface -> build_manifest with {
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}",
    doc_files: "{{outputs.scan_docs.doc_files}}",
    cli_commands: "{{outputs.scan_code_surface.cli_commands}}",
    cli_flags: "{{outputs.scan_code_surface.cli_flags}}",
    diagnostic_codes: "{{outputs.scan_code_surface.diagnostic_codes}}",
    code_scope_globs: "{{vars.code_scope_globs}}",
    max_drift_candidates: "{{vars.max_drift_candidates}}",
    max_review_chunk_docs: "{{vars.max_review_chunk_docs}}"
  }
  build_manifest -> alt

  ## Round-robin alternates: 1st pass → claude, 2nd → gpt, repeat.
  ## v0.15.0: reviewers consume the BOUNDED manifest output
  ## (drift_candidates + summary stats) instead of the v0.14.0
  ## bulk shape (doc_files / pre_verified_docs / cli_commands / …
  ## that grew with the doc footprint). Cross-family pushback +
  ## chronic-path signals carry through unchanged.
  alt -> reviewer_claude with {
    total_docs: "{{outputs.build_manifest.total_docs}}",
    total_anchors: "{{outputs.build_manifest.total_anchors}}",
    verified_anchors: "{{outputs.build_manifest.verified_anchors}}",
    drifted_anchors: "{{outputs.build_manifest.drifted_anchors}}",
    unverifiable_anchors: "{{outputs.build_manifest.unverifiable_anchors}}",
    manifest_coverage_pct: "{{outputs.build_manifest.coverage_pct}}",
    drift_candidates: "{{outputs.build_manifest.drift_candidates}}",
    per_doc_anchor_counts: "{{outputs.build_manifest.per_doc_anchor_counts}}",
    all_audited_docs: "{{outputs.build_manifest.all_audited_docs}}",
    docs_with_drift_count: "{{outputs.build_manifest.docs_with_drift_count}}",
    chunked: "{{outputs.build_manifest.chunked}}",
    chunk_doc_count: "{{outputs.build_manifest.chunk_doc_count}}",
    max_review_chunk_docs: "{{outputs.build_manifest.max_review_chunk_docs}}",
    coverage_target_pct: "{{vars.coverage_target_pct}}",
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback_justification}}",
    prior_code_files_touched_claude: "{{outputs.fix_claude.code_files_touched}}",
    prior_code_files_touched_gpt: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.code_files_touched}}",
    cumulative_chronic_paths: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_chronic_paths}}",
    ## v0.17.0 do-not-relitigate inputs (cumulative across the
    ## entire run, not just the last iter).
    cumulative_dismissed_pairs: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_dismissed_pairs}}",
    cumulative_pushback: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_pushback}}"
  }
  alt -> reviewer_gpt with {
    total_docs: "{{outputs.build_manifest.total_docs}}",
    total_anchors: "{{outputs.build_manifest.total_anchors}}",
    verified_anchors: "{{outputs.build_manifest.verified_anchors}}",
    drifted_anchors: "{{outputs.build_manifest.drifted_anchors}}",
    unverifiable_anchors: "{{outputs.build_manifest.unverifiable_anchors}}",
    manifest_coverage_pct: "{{outputs.build_manifest.coverage_pct}}",
    drift_candidates: "{{outputs.build_manifest.drift_candidates}}",
    per_doc_anchor_counts: "{{outputs.build_manifest.per_doc_anchor_counts}}",
    all_audited_docs: "{{outputs.build_manifest.all_audited_docs}}",
    docs_with_drift_count: "{{outputs.build_manifest.docs_with_drift_count}}",
    chunked: "{{outputs.build_manifest.chunked}}",
    chunk_doc_count: "{{outputs.build_manifest.chunk_doc_count}}",
    max_review_chunk_docs: "{{outputs.build_manifest.max_review_chunk_docs}}",
    coverage_target_pct: "{{vars.coverage_target_pct}}",
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback_justification}}",
    prior_code_files_touched_claude: "{{outputs.fix_claude.code_files_touched}}",
    prior_code_files_touched_gpt: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.code_files_touched}}",
    cumulative_chronic_paths: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_chronic_paths}}",
    ## v0.17.0 do-not-relitigate inputs (cumulative across the
    ## entire run, not just the last iter).
    cumulative_dismissed_pairs: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_dismissed_pairs}}",
    cumulative_pushback: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_pushback}}"
    ## v0.7.0 cost optimisation moot under the manifest shape —
    ## input is now bounded, no more cumulative context bloat to
    ## fight. Keeping session: fresh on reviewer_gpt for the
    ## fixed-size guarantee. (_session_id intentionally absent.)
  }

  reviewer_claude -> streak_check as review_loop(15) with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.blockers}}",
    blocker_count: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.blocker_count}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.confidence}}",
    audited_pairs: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.audited_pairs}}",
    audited_docs: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.audited_docs}}",
    ## v0.12.0+v0.13.0: carry the last enforce_fix_scope reverts
    ## (raw history, kept for telemetry) AND its chronic_paths
    ## (thresholded, fed forward to next reviewer).
    ## v0.14.0: also carry the per-iter declared echo so streak_check
    ## can union it into cumulative_declared_paths and keep iter N's
    ## newly-declared files alive across the next iter's revert pass.
    enforce_reverted_paths: "{{outputs.enforce_fix_scope.reverted_paths}}",
    enforce_chronic_paths: "{{outputs.enforce_fix_scope.chronic_paths}}",
    enforce_declared_iter: "{{outputs.enforce_fix_scope.declared_iter}}"
  }
  reviewer_gpt -> streak_check as review_loop(15) with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.blockers}}",
    blocker_count: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.blocker_count}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.confidence}}",
    audited_pairs: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.audited_pairs}}",
    audited_docs: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.audited_docs}}",
    enforce_reverted_paths: "{{outputs.enforce_fix_scope.reverted_paths}}",
    enforce_chronic_paths: "{{outputs.enforce_fix_scope.chronic_paths}}",
    enforce_declared_iter: "{{outputs.enforce_fix_scope.declared_iter}}"
  }

  ## Stop on (cross-family double approval) AND (coverage gate met).
  ## EFFICIENCY: route the converged streak through a deterministic
  ## has-changes guard — run the LLM prepare_commit only when the fixers
  ## actually changed the tree; a review-only (no-fix) convergence skips to
  ## the audit-cache refresh + done.
  streak_check -> detect_doc_changes when stop

  detect_doc_changes -> prepare_commit when has_changes
  detect_doc_changes -> update_audit_cache when not has_changes with {
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}",
    cache_path: "{{vars.audit_cache_path}}",
    audited_pairs: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_audited_pairs}}"
  }

  prepare_commit -> commit_changes with {
    full_message: "{{outputs.prepare_commit.full_message}}",
    files: "{{outputs.prepare_commit.files}}",
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}"
  }

  ## v0.5.0: inter-run cache is updated AFTER a successful commit
  ## so a failed commit doesn't poison the cache with un-shipped
  ## audit state. update_audit_cache is a deterministic tool
  ## (no LLM cost) so this adds ~ms to the run.
  commit_changes -> mark_issue_for_review
  mark_issue_for_review -> update_audit_cache with {
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}",
    cache_path: "{{vars.audit_cache_path}}",
    audited_pairs: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_audited_pairs}}"
  }

  update_audit_cache -> done

  ## Soft-approval (no streak yet, or low-confidence rejection):
  ## keep alternating without invoking the fixer.
  streak_check -> alt when "approved"

  ## Medium/high-confidence rejection with concrete blockers:
  ## route to the SAME-family fixer (inherit reviewer's session
  ## via _session_id). v0.3.0: blocker_count > 0 replaces
  ## length(blockers) > 0 — the latter measures the JSON-encoded
  ## string length (always > 0 for any output, even "[]"),
  ## so the previous guard was effectively no-op when approved=false.
  streak_check -> fix_claude when "!approved && family == 'claude' && blocker_count > 0" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude._session_id}}"
  }
  streak_check -> fix_gpt when "!approved && family == 'gpt' && blocker_count > 0" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt._session_id}}"
  }

  ## v0.11.0: interpose enforce_fix_scope between fix_* and alt
  ## so out-of-declaration edits are reverted before the next
  ## reviewer sees them. The loop counter follows the inbound
  ## edge — recovery_loop still bounds total fix attempts at 20.
  ## v0.13.0: also feed the cumulative revert history forward so
  ## the tool can compute chronic_paths itself.
  fix_claude -> enforce_fix_scope as recovery_loop(20) with {
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}",
    declared_paths: "{{outputs.fix_claude.modified_doc_files}}",
    cumulative_so_far: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_reverted_paths}}",
    cumulative_so_far_declared: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_declared_paths}}"
  }
  fix_gpt -> enforce_fix_scope as recovery_loop(20) with {
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}",
    declared_paths: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.modified_doc_files}}",
    cumulative_so_far: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_reverted_paths}}",
    cumulative_so_far_declared: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_declared_paths}}"
  }
  ## v0.15.0: re-run build_manifest after each fix iter so the
  ## reviewer's drift_candidates set reflects the fresh worktree
  ## state. The with{} mirrors the initial-flow edge — same
  ## input shape, same target node.
  enforce_fix_scope -> build_manifest with {
    workspace_dir: "{{vars.workspace_dir}}",
    doc_files: "{{outputs.scan_docs.doc_files}}",
    cli_commands: "{{outputs.scan_code_surface.cli_commands}}",
    cli_flags: "{{outputs.scan_code_surface.cli_flags}}",
    diagnostic_codes: "{{outputs.scan_code_surface.diagnostic_codes}}",
    code_scope_globs: "{{vars.code_scope_globs}}",
    max_drift_candidates: "{{vars.max_drift_candidates}}",
    max_review_chunk_docs: "{{vars.max_review_chunk_docs}}"
  }

  ## Loop-exhaustion fallthroughs: the bounded review_loop /
  ## recovery_loop was used up WITHOUT streak_check ever firing `stop`
  ## — i.e. no convergence and no commit. Route to `fail`, NOT `done`,
  ## so the run reports `failed` instead of a silent empty success.
  ## Otherwise the dispatcher's completed_state marks the ticket
  ## `review` as if doc work landed, and a coverage-gate deadlock
  ## (reviewers approve while coverage < target, so the fixer never
  ## fires to raise it) is indistinguishable from a clean convergence.
  ## The legitimate success path is streak_check → prepare_commit →
  ## commit_changes → mark_issue_for_review → update_audit_cache → done
  ## (declared above); `fail` is non-resumable so the dispatcher won't
  ## re-dispatch a deterministic non-convergence in a loop.
  reviewer_claude -> fail
  reviewer_gpt    -> fail
  fix_claude      -> fail
  fix_gpt         -> fail
  streak_check    -> alt
